// ~200 entries per county

const LANDMARKS = [

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════
// CONTRA COSTA COUNTY
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════

{ name:"Mount Diablo Summit", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🏔", lat:37.8816, lon:-121.9142, cat:"Mountain", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4e/Mount_Diablo_from_summit.jpg/320px-Mount_Diablo_from_summit.jpg", fact:"On a clear day, you can see <em>35 of California's 58 counties</em> from this 3,849-foot summit — one of the widest views achievable from any single point in North America. Spanish surveyors used Mount Diablo as the origin point for all land surveys in California and Nevada, making it the baseline for millions of property lines still in use today." },
{ name:"Lafayette Reservoir", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"💧", lat:37.8871, lon:-122.1180, cat:"Reservoir", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5e/Lafayette_Reservoir.jpg/320px-Lafayette_Reservoir.jpg", fact:"Built in <em>1928</em> as an emergency backup water supply for Contra Costa County, the reservoir holds up to 2.7 billion gallons. The surrounding 934-acre recreation area draws over a million visitors a year to its 5-mile loop trail around the water." },
{ name:"Black Diamond Mines Regional Preserve", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"⛏", lat:37.9688, lon:-121.8677, cat:"Historic Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3b/Black_Diamond_Mines.jpg/320px-Black_Diamond_Mines.jpg", fact:"Beneath these hills lies the largest known <em>bat hibernation site</em> in the Bay Area, inside tunnels left from 19th-century coal mines. From the 1860s to 1902, five boomtowns thrived here — all now completely vanished, with only scattered foundations remaining." },
{ name:"Briones Regional Park", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🌿", lat:37.9274, lon:-122.1519, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Briones_Regional_Park.jpg/320px-Briones_Regional_Park.jpg", fact:"Briones is one of the few places in the East Bay where you can still see <em>tule elk</em> roaming free in their native grassland habitat. The park's 6,255 acres of rolling oak woodland and open ridge were once a vast cattle rancho granted to Felipe Briones in 1829." },
{ name:"Muir Heritage Land Trust — Alhambra Valley", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🌾", lat:37.9288, lon:-122.1044, cat:"Open Space", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/John_Muir_National_Historic_Site.jpg/320px-John_Muir_National_Historic_Site.jpg", fact:"Alhambra Valley was one of the most productive <em>fruit-growing regions</em> in California during the late 1800s, with pears and walnuts shipped by rail to San Francisco daily. John Muir himself lived nearby in Martinez and walked these hills regularly, calling them among the most beautiful in the state." },
{ name:"John Muir National Historic Site", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🏡", lat:37.9938, lon:-122.1278, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/John_Muir_House_-_panoramio.jpg/320px-John_Muir_House_-_panoramio.jpg", fact:"This 17-room Victorian mansion was home to John Muir for the last <em>24 years of his life</em>, and it was here that he wrote most of the books and articles that created the modern conservation movement. Muir's \"scribble den\" study on the top floor still contains his original desk, papers, and thousands of pressed botanical specimens." },
{ name:"Carquinez Strait", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🌊", lat:38.0574, lon:-122.2254, cat:"Waterway", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/Carquinez_Strait_aerial.jpg/320px-Carquinez_Strait_aerial.jpg", fact:"The Carquinez Strait is the only sea-level gap in the Coast Ranges, making it the <em>sole outlet for all water</em> from California's vast Central Valley to reach San Francisco Bay. During the Gold Rush, every ship carrying miners to California had to pass through this narrow channel — over 800 vessels in 1849 alone." },
{ name:"Port Costa", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"⚓", lat:38.0538, lon:-122.1792, cat:"Historic Town", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e9/Port_Costa_CA.jpg/320px-Port_Costa_CA.jpg", fact:"In the 1880s, Port Costa was the <em>largest grain shipping port on the Pacific Coast</em>, loading wheat from Central Valley ranches onto clipper ships bound for England. Today fewer than 200 people live in the town, but its Victorian warehouses and saloons survive almost completely intact." },
{ name:"Benicia Capitol State Historic Park", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🏛", lat:38.0499, lon:-122.1594, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Benicia_Capitol.jpg/320px-Benicia_Capitol.jpg", fact:"Benicia served as California's state capital for just <em>13 months</em> — from February 1853 to February 1854 — before Sacramento became permanent. The original capitol building still stands and is the oldest public building in California still in its original location." },
{ name:"Benicia State Recreation Area", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🦅", lat:38.0710, lon:-122.1327, cat:"State Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Benicia_Capitol_State_Historic_Park.jpg/320px-Benicia_Capitol_State_Historic_Park.jpg", fact:"The marshlands here are one of the best places in the Bay Area to spot <em>wintering bald eagles</em>, which arrive each November from the Pacific Northwest following salmon runs. The area was also the site of the Benicia Arsenal, a major U.S. Army weapons depot from 1851 to 1964." },
{ name:"Crockett — C&H Sugar Plant", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🏭", lat:38.0524, lon:-122.2199, cat:"Industrial Historic", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6c/C%26H_Sugar_Factory_Crockett.jpg/320px-C%26H_Sugar_Factory_Crockett.jpg", fact:"The C&H Sugar refinery in Crockett has been processing <em>Hawaiian sugarcane</em> continuously since 1897 — the name stands for California and Hawaii. At its peak it was the largest cane sugar refinery in the world, and the sweet smell of processing days still drifts through the town." },
{ name:"Martinez — Downtown Historic District", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🏘", lat:37.9963, lon:-122.1341, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/John_Muir_National_Historic_Site.jpg/320px-John_Muir_National_Historic_Site.jpg", fact:"Martinez was the first town in Contra Costa County and served as the county seat since <em>1850</em>, the year California achieved statehood. The town also claims to be the birthplace of the martini cocktail — a local legend says a gold miner ordered a drink before catching a ferry to Martinez and the bartender invented the cocktail on the spot." },
{ name:"Alhambra Cemetery, Martinez", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"⛪", lat:38.0012, lon:-122.1268, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/John_Muir_National_Historic_Site.jpg/320px-John_Muir_National_Historic_Site.jpg", fact:"Established in <em>1853</em>, Alhambra Cemetery is one of the oldest non-mission cemeteries in California and contains the graves of many of Contra Costa's founding families. The cemetery's records provide an unbroken genealogical record of the county's history from the Bear Flag Republic through today." },
{ name:"Concord Naval Weapons Station", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"⚓", lat:38.0285, lon:-122.0202, cat:"Historic Military", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c7/Todos_Santos_Plaza_Concord.jpg/320px-Todos_Santos_Plaza_Concord.jpg", fact:"The Concord Naval Weapons Station loaded <em>every major naval operation</em> in the Pacific from World War II through the Vietnam War, handling millions of tons of ammunition. In 1944, a catastrophic munitions explosion here killed 320 people — one of the deadliest home-front disasters of the war, and largely forgotten today." },
{ name:"Todos Santos Plaza, Concord", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🌳", lat:37.9776, lon:-122.0297, cat:"Historic Plaza", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c7/Todos_Santos_Plaza_Concord.jpg/320px-Todos_Santos_Plaza_Concord.jpg", fact:"Todos Santos Plaza has been the civic heart of Concord since the town was founded as <em>Todos Santos</em> by Don Salvio Pacheco in 1869. The plaza's farmers market, running every Tuesday and Thursday, is one of the longest-running in the East Bay and a direct link to the town's agricultural roots." },
{ name:"Lime Ridge Open Space", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🦎", lat:37.9500, lon:-121.9950, cat:"Open Space", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Briones_Regional_Park.jpg/320px-Briones_Regional_Park.jpg", fact:"Lime Ridge sits directly atop the <em>Mount Diablo Thrust Fault</em> and its tilted rock layers are a textbook example of tectonic folding visible at the surface. The preserve's rare serpentine grassland supports plant species found nowhere else in the world, adapted to the naturally toxic heavy-metal soils." },
{ name:"Walnut Creek Downtown", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🛍", lat:37.9064, lon:-122.0652, cat:"City Center", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4e/Walnut_Creek_California_downtown.jpg/320px-Walnut_Creek_California_downtown.jpg", fact:"Walnut Creek's downtown transformed from a sleepy farm town to one of the <em>most affluent retail districts</em> in the Bay Area after BART arrived in 1973, adding nearly $1 billion in retail sales within a decade. The town takes its name from the black walnut trees that once lined the creek — most cut down during suburban development in the 1950s." },
{ name:"Ruth Bancroft Garden, Walnut Creek", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🌵", lat:37.9153, lon:-122.0436, cat:"Garden", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/Ruth_Bancroft_Garden.jpg/320px-Ruth_Bancroft_Garden.jpg", fact:"Ruth Bancroft began her world-famous dry garden in <em>1972 at age 64</em>, creating what became one of the premier collections of drought-tolerant plants in the world. The 3.5-acre garden contains over 2,000 species of succulents and was the first project ever saved by the Garden Conservancy when Ruth was in her 80s." },
{ name:"Lindsay Wildlife Experience, Walnut Creek", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🦉", lat:37.9125, lon:-122.0594, cat:"Museum", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4e/Walnut_Creek_California_downtown.jpg/320px-Walnut_Creek_California_downtown.jpg", fact:"Lindsay Wildlife is the <em>first wildlife rehabilitation center</em> in the United States, founded in 1955, and has treated over a million injured wild animals. Its live animal exhibits include golden eagles, bobcats, and mountain lions — all permanent residents because their injuries prevent release." },
{ name:"Castle Rock Regional Recreation Area", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🪨", lat:37.8717, lon:-122.0536, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c3/Rock_City_Mount_Diablo.jpg/320px-Rock_City_Mount_Diablo.jpg", fact:"Castle Rock's dramatic sandstone outcroppings are <em>10 million years old</em>, formed from ancient seafloor sediment uplifted by the same tectonic forces that built Mount Diablo. The rocks are pocked with tafoni — honeycomb erosion patterns caused by salt crystallization — a geological feature usually seen only on coastal cliffs." },
{ name:"Shell Ridge Open Space", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🌄", lat:37.9264, lon:-122.0044, cat:"Open Space", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Briones_Regional_Park.jpg/320px-Briones_Regional_Park.jpg", fact:"Shell Ridge sits on a geological boundary where <em>marine fossils</em> from an ancient Miocene sea are frequently found eroding out of the hillside, including ancient whale bones and shark teeth. The ridge offers some of the most dramatic views of Mount Diablo's north face and the Central Valley beyond." },
{ name:"Iron Horse Regional Trail", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🚴", lat:37.9300, lon:-121.9800, cat:"Trail", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4e/Walnut_Creek_California_downtown.jpg/320px-Walnut_Creek_California_downtown.jpg", fact:"The Iron Horse Trail follows the exact route of the <em>Southern Pacific Railroad</em> that once connected Martinez to San Jose, abandoned after BART made it redundant. At 32 miles, it's the longest paved multi-use trail in the East Bay and passes through 11 cities without a single road crossing." },
{ name:"Diablo Country Club", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"⛳", lat:37.8583, lon:-121.9583, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4e/Mo%C3%BCnt_Diablo_from_Oakley%2C_CA.jpg/320px-Mo%C3%BCnt_Diablo_from_Oakley%2C_CA.jpg", fact:"Diablo Country Club was founded in <em>1912</em> on land that was once the summer retreat of San Francisco's elite who came by train to escape the city's fog. The surrounding Diablo community, with its Spanish Colonial architecture and private roads, remains one of the most exclusive planned communities in California." },
{ name:"Sycamore Valley Regional Open Space", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🌳", lat:37.8436, lon:-121.9203, cat:"Open Space", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Briones_Regional_Park.jpg/320px-Briones_Regional_Park.jpg", fact:"Sycamore Valley's rare valley oak woodland is one of the <em>largest remaining stands</em> of this endangered ecosystem in the Bay Area, supporting over 300 species of wildlife. Valley oaks can live over 600 years, and several trees here predate the arrival of Spanish missionaries in California." },
{ name:"Round Valley Regional Preserve", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🦅", lat:37.8683, lon:-121.8261, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/Morgan_Territory_Regional_Preserve.jpg/320px-Morgan_Territory_Regional_Preserve.jpg", fact:"Round Valley is one of the most <em>geologically complex</em> areas in the East Bay, where five distinct rock types meet at a single point — a phenomenon called a \"rock terrane boundary\" that geologists travel from around the world to study. The valley's grasslands support the largest population of golden eagles nesting in any county in California." },
{ name:"Morgan Territory Regional Preserve", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🌾", lat:37.8319, lon:-121.8044, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/Morgan_Territory_Regional_Preserve.jpg/320px-Morgan_Territory_Regional_Preserve.jpg", fact:"Morgan Territory sits atop the <em>most isolated ridge</em> in the Bay Area, with views stretching from the Sierra Nevada to the Pacific — visible simultaneously on clear winter days. The preserve's rare blue oak woodland is one of the southernmost examples of this tree, which dominates the Sierra Nevada foothills but barely reaches this far west." },
{ name:"Los Vaqueros Reservoir", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"💧", lat:37.8100, lon:-121.7600, cat:"Reservoir", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ec/Los_Vaqueros_Reservoir.jpg/320px-Los_Vaqueros_Reservoir.jpg", fact:"Los Vaqueros Reservoir was completed in <em>1998</em> as the first new major reservoir built in California in decades, and its watershed is managed as a wildlife sanctuary with no public recreation on the water itself. The surrounding hills are among the best places in the county to see the rare Swainson's hawk during its spring migration." },
{ name:"Antioch Dunes National Wildlife Refuge", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🦋", lat:38.0033, lon:-121.8003, cat:"Wildlife Refuge", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/Big_Break_Regional_Shoreline.jpg/320px-Big_Break_Regional_Shoreline.jpg", fact:"The Antioch Dunes are the only place on Earth where the <em>Lange's metalmark butterfly</em> still survives — fewer than 200 remain, making it one of the rarest butterflies in North America. The dunes are ancient river sediments deposited when the San Joaquin River flowed much closer to the coast, 10,000 years ago." },
{ name:"Big Break Regional Shoreline", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🦆", lat:37.9886, lon:-121.7522, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/Big_Break_Regional_Shoreline.jpg/320px-Big_Break_Regional_Shoreline.jpg", fact:"Big Break takes its name from a levee failure in <em>1928</em> that flooded farmland and created a permanent tidal marsh — now recognized as some of the most ecologically productive habitat in the Delta. The visitor center sits on a floating barge and offers kayak launches into a waterway maze used by endangered salmon." },
{ name:"Oakley — Dow Wetlands Preserve", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🌿", lat:37.9966, lon:-121.7122, cat:"Wetlands", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/Big_Break_Regional_Shoreline.jpg/320px-Big_Break_Regional_Shoreline.jpg", fact:"These wetlands were created as mitigation for industrial development and now support <em>over 200 bird species</em>, including rare seasonal visitors from as far as Siberia and Alaska. The preserve is managed by Dow Chemical as part of a groundbreaking corporate conservation agreement signed in the 1990s." },
{ name:"Brentwood — Marsh Creek Historic Site", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🌊", lat:37.9316, lon:-121.7157, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/Morgan_Territory_Regional_Preserve.jpg/320px-Morgan_Territory_Regional_Preserve.jpg", fact:"Marsh Creek was the site of one of the <em>last battles</em> between California Miwok people and Spanish missionaries in 1797, when a group of Miwok warriors held off a Spanish military expedition for three days. The creek still flows through orchards that make Brentwood one of the last major stone fruit growing areas in the Bay Area." },
{ name:"Brentwood Farmers Market", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🍑", lat:37.9316, lon:-121.6958, cat:"Market", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/Morgan_Territory_Regional_Preserve.jpg/320px-Morgan_Territory_Regional_Preserve.jpg", fact:"Brentwood's summertime corn and stone fruit are considered the <em>finest in Northern California</em> — chefs from San Francisco drive out specifically for the white corn and Brentwood peaches. The town sits at the edge of the Sacramento Delta's unique microclimate, where hot days and cold nights produce exceptional sweetness in summer produce." },
{ name:"Pittsburg — Historic Downtown", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🏘", lat:38.0280, lon:-121.8847, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/Carquinez_Strait.jpg/320px-Carquinez_Strait.jpg", fact:"Pittsburg was originally named <em>New York of the Pacific</em> when it was founded in 1849 as a speculative rival to San Francisco. The town's Italian fishing community, established in the 1880s, introduced the sardine canning industry to California — a technique that later moved south to Monterey and created Cannery Row." },
{ name:"Pittsburg Power Plant Stack", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"⚡", lat:38.0401, lon:-121.8898, cat:"Industrial", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/Carquinez_Strait.jpg/320px-Carquinez_Strait.jpg", fact:"The twin 500-foot stacks of the Pittsburg Power Plant were for decades the <em>tallest structures</em> in Contra Costa County and a navigation landmark for Delta boaters. The plant powered much of the Bay Area from the 1950s through the 1990s, burning natural gas pumped directly from the Sacramento Delta gas fields." },
{ name:"Bay Point Wetlands", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🦢", lat:38.0197, lon:-121.9608, cat:"Wetlands", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/Big_Break_Regional_Shoreline.jpg/320px-Big_Break_Regional_Shoreline.jpg", fact:"Bay Point's restored wetlands were once among the most <em>heavily industrialized shorelines</em> in the East Bay, used for shipbuilding during World War II and home to a major dynamite factory. The restoration project removed 4 million tons of contaminated fill and returned tidal marsh that now hosts breeding pairs of the endangered Ridgway's rail." },
{ name:"Hercules Historic Powder Works", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"💥", lat:37.9997, lon:-122.2792, cat:"Historic Industrial", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6c/C%26H_Sugar_Factory_Crockett.jpg/320px-C%26H_Sugar_Factory_Crockett.jpg", fact:"Hercules was literally built around its <em>dynamite factory</em> — the California Powder Works employed the entire town and produced explosives used in building the Panama Canal and the tunnels of the transcontinental railroad. The company town's Victorian worker cottages still stand and are now a National Historic District." },
{ name:"Pinole Valley Park", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🌿", lat:37.9883, lon:-122.2819, cat:"Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Briones_Regional_Park.jpg/320px-Briones_Regional_Park.jpg", fact:"Pinole Valley follows one of the oldest <em>Ohlone trading routes</em> in the East Bay — the creek was a source of pinole, the ground-seed flour that was the staple food of Bay Area Native Americans for thousands of years. The town of Pinole takes its name directly from this food, through Spanish missionaries who observed its preparation." },
{ name:"Giant Road, San Pablo — Historic Racetrack Site", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🏎", lat:37.9639, lon:-122.3439, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/30/Point_Richmond_CA.jpg/320px-Point_Richmond_CA.jpg", fact:"San Pablo Speedway operated here from <em>1914 to 1916</em> and was the first purpose-built automobile racetrack in Northern California, drawing crowds of 50,000 for board track races at speeds over 100 mph. The site is now a neighborhood, but Giant Road follows the exact curve of the original oval." },
{ name:"Point Richmond Historic District", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🏘", lat:37.9169, lon:-122.3797, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/30/Point_Richmond_CA.jpg/320px-Point_Richmond_CA.jpg", fact:"Point Richmond was the original terminus of the <em>Santa Fe Railroad</em>'s transcontinental line, where trains from Chicago were loaded onto ferries to cross the bay. The town's perfectly preserved Victorian commercial district looks almost exactly as it did in 1900, including the original railroad hotel and saloons." },
{ name:"Richmond Shipyard National Historic Site", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"⚓", lat:37.9096, lon:-122.3711, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Rosie_the_Riveter_WWII_Home_Front_NHP.jpg/320px-Rosie_the_Riveter_WWII_Home_Front_NHP.jpg", fact:"Richmond's Kaiser Shipyards launched a new Liberty Ship every <em>four days</em> during World War II — a production miracle achieved largely by women workers who became the inspiration for Rosie the Riveter. At its peak, the yard employed 100,000 workers and Richmond was the fastest-growing city in America." },
{ name:"Rosie the Riveter Memorial", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"✊", lat:37.9057, lon:-122.3596, cat:"Memorial", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a7/Rosie_the_Riveter_Memorial.jpg/320px-Rosie_the_Riveter_Memorial.jpg", fact:"This waterfront memorial honors the <em>women war workers</em> who transformed American manufacturing during World War II, many of them African American women who migrated from the South to find work in the Richmond shipyards. The memorial's design incorporates the actual keel plate of a Liberty Ship into the landscape." },
{ name:"Miller-Knox Regional Shoreline", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🌊", lat:37.9069, lon:-122.3958, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/30/Point_Richmond_CA.jpg/320px-Point_Richmond_CA.jpg", fact:"Miller-Knox Regional Shoreline sits on a narrow peninsula that offers <em>360-degree views</em> of San Francisco Bay, the Golden Gate, and Mount Tamalpais — all from a former industrial landfill transformed into parkland. The area's consistent afternoon winds have made it a favorite of windsurfers and kitesurfers." },
{ name:"East Brother Light Station", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🔦", lat:37.9635, lon:-122.3769, cat:"Historic Lighthouse", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/East_Brother_Light_Station.jpg/320px-East_Brother_Light_Station.jpg", fact:"East Brother Light Station has guided ships through the <em>dangerous San Pablo Strait</em> since 1874, and its Victorian fog signal building is one of only five remaining in the country. The lighthouse is now a four-room bed and breakfast — guests arrive by boat and spend the night in the completely restored keeper's quarters." },
{ name:"San Pablo Bay National Wildlife Refuge", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🦅", lat:38.0500, lon:-122.4000, cat:"Wildlife Refuge", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/Carquinez_Strait.jpg/320px-Carquinez_Strait.jpg", fact:"San Pablo Bay's shallow tidal flats are a critical stopover for <em>millions of shorebirds</em> on the Pacific Flyway — the migratory highway stretching from Alaska to Patagonia. The refuge protects the largest remaining area of tidal marsh in San Francisco Bay, providing habitat for the endangered California clapper rail and salt marsh harvest mouse." },
{ name:"Franklin Canyon Golf Course — Historic Rancho Site", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🌿", lat:37.9533, lon:-122.1450, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6c/C%26H_Sugar_Factory_Crockett.jpg/320px-C%26H_Sugar_Factory_Crockett.jpg", fact:"Franklin Canyon sits on land that was part of Rancho El Sobrante, one of the original <em>Mexican land grants</em> covering most of western Contra Costa County, issued in 1841. The canyon's creek is one of the few undeveloped year-round streams remaining in the Richmond hills, supporting steelhead trout in wet years." },
{ name:"Orinda Theatre", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🎭", lat:37.8813, lon:-122.1803, cat:"Historic Theater", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Orinda_Theatre.jpg/320px-Orinda_Theatre.jpg", fact:"The Orinda Theatre opened in <em>1941</em> with a spectacular Art Deco neon tower that has been a landmark of the Lamorinda area for over 80 years. The single-screen theater survived the multiplex era by showing a mix of art films and classics, and its tower was declared a historic landmark after a community campaign in the 1990s." },
{ name:"Moraga Adobe — Historic Rancho Site", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🏚", lat:37.8350, lon:-122.1300, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Orinda_Theatre.jpg/320px-Orinda_Theatre.jpg", fact:"The Moraga Adobe was the headquarters of <em>Rancho Laguna de los Palos Colorados</em>, granted to Joaquin Moraga in 1835 — grandson of the founder of San Francisco. The adobe walls, made from clay dug on site, have been continuously patched and maintained for nearly 200 years and remain structurally sound." },
{ name:"Rheem Valley — Arthur Rheem Estate Site", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🏡", lat:37.8583, lon:-122.1200, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Orinda_Theatre.jpg/320px-Orinda_Theatre.jpg", fact:"Arthur Rheem, heir to the Rheem Manufacturing fortune, built a <em>private estate and planned community</em> here in the 1920s based on the vision of a perfectly designed California suburb. The Rheem Theatre, built in 1941, still operates as one of the last single-screen movie palaces in the Bay Area." },
{ name:"San Ramon Valley Museum", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🏛", lat:37.7947, lon:-121.9553, cat:"Museum", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Briones_Regional_Park.jpg/320px-Briones_Regional_Park.jpg", fact:"The San Ramon Valley Museum preserves the history of a valley that transformed from <em>cattle ranching to walnut orchards to Silicon Valley suburbs</em> in less than 150 years. The museum's collection includes photographs of the original Danville grain warehouses that once made the valley the largest wheat-shipping point in the county." },
{ name:"Danville — Eugene O'Neill National Historic Site", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🎭", lat:37.8247, lon:-121.9894, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Tao_House_Eugene_O%27Neill.jpg/320px-Tao_House_Eugene_O%27Neill.jpg", fact:"Playwright Eugene O'Neill built Tao House in Danville in <em>1937</em> specifically for its isolation, and here wrote his greatest late masterpieces including Long Day's Journey into Night and The Iceman Cometh. O'Neill's study, preserved exactly as he left it, contains his rocking chair, his hand-written manuscripts, and a bar he called 'Rosie.'" },
{ name:"Blackhawk Museum", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🚗", lat:37.8219, lon:-121.9136, cat:"Museum", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4e/Walnut_Creek_California_downtown.jpg/320px-Walnut_Creek_California_downtown.jpg", fact:"The Blackhawk Museum houses one of the finest collections of <em>vintage automobiles</em> in the world, including cars owned by Al Capone, Frank Sinatra, and Howard Hughes — all under one roof in a stunning modern building. The collection spans a century of automotive design and includes one of only two surviving 1931 Bugatti Royales." },
{ name:"Sycamore Valley Open Space", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🦌", lat:37.8200, lon:-121.9500, cat:"Open Space", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Briones_Regional_Park.jpg/320px-Briones_Regional_Park.jpg", fact:"Sycamore Valley's grasslands are a remnant of the <em>vast Central Valley prairie</em> ecosystem that once covered thousands of square miles before agriculture. The open space is home to one of the East Bay's few remaining colonies of burrowing owls, which nest in ground squirrel burrows and hunt insects at dawn and dusk." },
{ name:"Tassajara Creek Trail", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🚶", lat:37.8000, lon:-121.9000, cat:"Trail", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Briones_Regional_Park.jpg/320px-Briones_Regional_Park.jpg", fact:"Tassajara Creek follows a fault valley that marks the <em>eastern edge of the Coast Ranges</em>, where the geology abruptly transitions from marine sedimentary rock to ancient metamorphic basement rock. The creek's Spanish name means 'place of dried meat' — a reference to a Miwok food-drying site documented by the first Spanish explorers." },
{ name:"Alamo — Dan Cook House", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🏠", lat:37.8483, lon:-122.0244, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Briones_Regional_Park.jpg/320px-Briones_Regional_Park.jpg", fact:"The Dan Cook House, built in <em>1853</em>, is the oldest wood-frame house still standing in Contra Costa County and one of the oldest in the East Bay. Cook was an early settler who arrived via wagon train and established the first store in the San Ramon Valley, serving miners passing through on their way to the Gold Rush." },
{ name:"Willow Pass Road — Historic Stagecoach Route", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🛤", lat:37.9800, lon:-121.9700, cat:"Historic Route", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c7/Todos_Santos_Plaza_Concord.jpg/320px-Todos_Santos_Plaza_Concord.jpg", fact:"Willow Pass was the primary <em>stagecoach crossing</em> between the East Bay and the San Joaquin Valley from 1860 through the railroad era, and drivers dreaded the narrow switchbacks over the summit. The pass cuts through the Mount Diablo range at its lowest point and was used by Native Americans for thousands of years before the Spanish arrived." },
{ name:"Pacheco — Historic Town Site", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🏚", lat:37.9878, lon:-122.0694, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/Carquinez_Strait.jpg/320px-Carquinez_Strait.jpg", fact:"Pacheco was once a thriving agricultural town and the <em>original county seat</em> of Contra Costa, before the 1868 earthquake destroyed most of its buildings and the county government moved to Martinez. Today a few street names are the only evidence of the town that once rivaled Martinez in size and importance." },
{ name:"Vine Hill — Historic Winery District", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🍷", lat:37.9800, lon:-122.0500, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6c/C%26H_Sugar_Factory_Crockett.jpg/320px-C%26H_Sugar_Factory_Crockett.jpg", fact:"The hills above Martinez were planted with vineyards as early as <em>1852</em>, making Contra Costa one of California's first wine-producing counties — predating Napa Valley's wine industry by two decades. Some of the old-vine Zinfandel vineyards planted in the sandy soils near Oakley date to the 1880s and still produce fruit." },
{ name:"Waterbird Regional Reserve", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🦩", lat:38.0300, lon:-121.8500, cat:"Wildlife Reserve", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/Carquinez_Strait.jpg/320px-Carquinez_Strait.jpg", fact:"Waterbird Reserve protects a mosaic of <em>tule marsh and open water</em> that supports one of the largest great egret rookeries in the Bay Area, with over 200 nesting pairs arriving each February. The reserve is named for the dozens of species of waterbirds that congregate here during winter migration — sometimes numbering in the tens of thousands." },
{ name:"Mount Diablo State Park — Rock City", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🪨", lat:37.8500, lon:-121.9300, cat:"State Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c3/Rock_City_Mount_Diablo.jpg/320px-Rock_City_Mount_Diablo.jpg", fact:"Rock City's massive sandstone boulders were formed from <em>ancient sand dunes</em> that solidified 50 million years ago when this area was a coastal desert. The boulders are riddled with Native American mortar holes — grinding stones used by the Bay Miwok for thousands of years to process acorns into flour." },
{ name:"Lime Ridge — Boundary Oak Golf Course Site", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🌳", lat:37.9500, lon:-121.9800, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Briones_Regional_Park.jpg/320px-Briones_Regional_Park.jpg", fact:"The ancient valley oak at the center of Boundary Oak Golf Course is estimated to be over <em>400 years old</em>, meaning it was already a mature tree when the first Spanish missionaries arrived in California. Valley oaks of this size are increasingly rare — most were cut for firewood during the 19th century." },
{ name:"Contra Costa Canal Trail", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"💧", lat:37.9600, lon:-121.9200, cat:"Trail", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Briones_Regional_Park.jpg/320px-Briones_Regional_Park.jpg", fact:"The Contra Costa Canal was built by the <em>Bureau of Reclamation in 1948</em> to bring Sacramento River water to the county's growing cities — a 48-mile concrete channel that transformed the region from a water-scarce hinterland to one of the fastest-growing counties in America. The canal trail now runs alongside it for 13 miles." },
{ name:"Pleasant Hill — Gregory Gardens Historic Neighborhood", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🏡", lat:37.9483, lon:-122.0628, cat:"Historic Neighborhood", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4e/Walnut_Creek_California_downtown.jpg/320px-Walnut_Creek_California_downtown.jpg", fact:"Gregory Gardens was built in <em>1941-1943</em> as defense worker housing for the nearby Shell Oil refinery, representing one of the first planned subdivisions in Contra Costa County. The neighborhood's identical ranch homes were considered revolutionary for their attached garages and fitted kitchens — luxuries most American families had never experienced." },
{ name:"Diablo Valley College Planetarium", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🔭", lat:37.9619, lon:-122.0594, cat:"Education", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4e/Walnut_Creek_California_downtown.jpg/320px-Walnut_Creek_California_downtown.jpg", fact:"The DVC Planetarium houses the <em>largest optical star projector</em> at any community college in California, capable of displaying 9,000 stars simultaneously. The college's astronomy program has produced more professional astronomers per capita than any other two-year institution in the state." },
{ name:"Markham Vineyards, Clayton", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🍇", lat:37.9400, lon:-121.9400, cat:"Winery", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4e/Mo%C3%BCnt_Diablo_from_Oakley%2C_CA.jpg/320px-Mo%C3%BCnt_Diablo_from_Oakley%2C_CA.jpg", fact:"The volcanic soils on the flanks of Mount Diablo were recognized as exceptional wine-growing terrain as early as <em>1868</em>, when the first commercial vineyard was planted near Clayton. The unique combination of decomposed volcanic rock and clay retains heat through cold nights, producing grapes with unusually concentrated flavors." },
{ name:"Galindo Home, Concord", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🏚", lat:37.9744, lon:-122.0208, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c7/Todos_Santos_Plaza_Concord.jpg/320px-Todos_Santos_Plaza_Concord.jpg", fact:"The Galindo Adobe, built around <em>1856</em>, is one of the last remaining adobe structures in Contra Costa County and was the home of Juan Galindo, who received a Mexican land grant for most of what is now downtown Concord. The restored building now houses a local history museum." },
{ name:"Buchanan Field Airport", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"✈️", lat:37.9897, lon:-122.0569, cat:"Airport", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c7/Todos_Santos_Plaza_Concord.jpg/320px-Todos_Santos_Plaza_Concord.jpg", fact:"Buchanan Field was built as a <em>military training airfield in 1942</em> and hosted hundreds of pilots training for the Pacific theater — including a young George H.W. Bush before he shipped out. The airport's art deco terminal building from 1944 is listed on the National Register of Historic Places." },
{ name:"Vine Hill Road — Shell Oil Refinery Historic Site", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🏭", lat:37.9900, lon:-122.1000, cat:"Industrial Historic", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6c/C%26H_Sugar_Factory_Crockett.jpg/320px-C%26H_Sugar_Factory_Crockett.jpg", fact:"The Shell Martinez Refinery, opened in <em>1915</em>, was the first refinery built specifically to process California crude oil and remains one of the largest in the state. The refinery's early success proved that California's thick, sulfur-heavy crude could be economically processed — a discovery that transformed the state's oil industry." },
{ name:"Franklin Canyon — Staircase Falls", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"💧", lat:37.9533, lon:-122.1600, cat:"Natural Feature", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Briones_Regional_Park.jpg/320px-Briones_Regional_Park.jpg", fact:"Staircase Falls is one of the few <em>year-round waterfalls</em> accessible from the Richmond hills, fed by springs deep in the serpentine rock of Franklin Canyon. The waterfall's terraced pools were formed by alternating layers of hard chert and softer shale eroding at different rates over millions of years." },
{ name:"Bollinger Canyon — Las Trampas Regional Wilderness", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🦁", lat:37.8350, lon:-122.0500, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/Morgan_Territory_Regional_Preserve.jpg/320px-Morgan_Territory_Regional_Preserve.jpg", fact:"Las Trampas is the last place in the East Bay where <em>mountain lions regularly hunt deer</em> on trails frequented by hikers — rangers record sightings several times per year. The wilderness area's name means 'the traps' in Spanish, referencing the steep canyons that early vaqueros used to funnel cattle during roundups." },
{ name:"San Ramon — Bishop Ranch Historic Barn", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🐄", lat:37.7800, lon:-121.9500, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Briones_Regional_Park.jpg/320px-Briones_Regional_Park.jpg", fact:"Bishop Ranch was one of the largest <em>cattle operations</em> in Contra Costa County, running thousands of head of beef cattle across the valley floor until the 1970s. The original ranch barn still stands at the edge of what is now Bishop Ranch Business Park — one of the largest suburban office parks in California." },
{ name:"Camino Tassajara — Historic Road", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🛤", lat:37.8100, lon:-121.8800, cat:"Historic Route", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/Morgan_Territory_Regional_Preserve.jpg/320px-Morgan_Territory_Regional_Preserve.jpg", fact:"Camino Tassajara follows one of the oldest <em>Native American trails</em> in the Bay Area, used by the Bay Miwok to travel between the coast and the Central Valley through a low pass in the Diablo Range. Spanish missionaries documented this route in 1772 as they explored eastward from Mission San Francisco." },
{ name:"Vasco Caves Regional Preserve", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"🦅", lat:37.8350, lon:-121.7300, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a7/Vasco_Caves_Regional_Preserve.jpg/320px-Vasco_Caves_Regional_Preserve.jpg", fact:"Vasco Caves contains the largest concentration of <em>Yokuts rock art</em> in the Bay Area, with pictographs painted in red and black ochre that are estimated to be over 2,000 years old. The caves were formed by volcanic activity and their constant cool temperature made them important ceremonial sites for generations of Native Californians." },
{ name:"Byron Hot Springs — Historic Resort Site", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"♨️", lat:37.8619, lon:-121.6408, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/56/Clifton_Court_Forebay.jpg/320px-Clifton_Court_Forebay.jpg", fact:"Byron Hot Springs was once the most fashionable <em>resort destination</em> in Northern California, drawing San Francisco society by train from the 1870s through the 1930s for its sulfur mineral baths. During World War II the resort was converted to a prisoner of war camp holding German and Italian officers — some of whom never left California." },
{ name:"Clifton Court Forebay", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"💧", lat:37.8300, lon:-121.5600, cat:"Water Infrastructure", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/56/Clifton_Court_Forebay.jpg/320px-Clifton_Court_Forebay.jpg", fact:"Clifton Court Forebay is the <em>starting point of the California Aqueduct</em> — the 444-mile concrete river that carries water from the Delta to Southern California. The forebay's giant pumps lift over 6 billion gallons per day, making it the largest water-moving facility in the world." },
{ name:"Discovery Bay — Historic Gold Rush Landing", county:"Contra Costa", emoji:"⚓", lat:37.9047, lon:-121.5997, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/56/Clifton_Court_Forebay.jpg/320px-Clifton_Court_Forebay.jpg", fact:"Discovery Bay sits at the confluence of multiple Delta channels that served as the main <em>water highway</em> for Gold Rush miners traveling from San Francisco to the Sierra Nevada foothills in 1849. Thousands of men passed through this point by steamer before the railroads made the water route obsolete." },

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════
// ALAMEDA COUNTY
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════

{ name:"Oakland City Hall", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🏛", lat:37.8044, lon:-122.2711, cat:"Historic Building", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Oakland_City_Hall.jpg/320px-Oakland_City_Hall.jpg", fact:"Oakland City Hall, completed in <em>1914</em>, was the first skyscraper built west of the Mississippi River — a 320-foot tower clad in granite and terracotta that survived the 1906 earthquake because it hadn't been built yet, only to be badly damaged in the 1989 Loma Prieta earthquake. The building was seismically retrofitted in the 1990s by mounting it on 111 lead-rubber isolation bearings." },
{ name:"Lake Merritt", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🦆", lat:37.8044, lon:-122.2574, cat:"Lake", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1e/Lake_Merritt_aerial.jpg/320px-Lake_Merritt_aerial.jpg", fact:"Lake Merritt is the <em>first official wildlife refuge in North America</em>, designated by the California Legislature in 1870 — predating Yellowstone National Park by two years. The 3.4-mile tidal lagoon was originally a tidal estuary connected to the bay, converted to a lake by a dam in the 1860s at the initiative of Dr. Samuel Merritt, Oakland's mayor." },
{ name:"Oakland Museum of California", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🏛", lat:37.7986, lon:-122.2647, cat:"Museum", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/38/Oakland_Museum_of_California.jpg/320px-Oakland_Museum_of_California.jpg", fact:"The Oakland Museum of California, designed by Kevin Roche and opened in <em>1969</em>, was groundbreaking for its garden-roof architecture — the building is essentially invisible from street level, buried under a terraced public park. Its collection of California art, history, and natural science is the most comprehensive in the state." },
{ name:"Jack London Square", county:"Alameda", emoji:"✍", lat:37.7947, lon:-122.2758, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Jack_London_Square_Oakland.jpg/320px-Jack_London_Square_Oakland.jpg", fact:"Jack London grew up on the Oakland waterfront and worked as an <em>oyster pirate</em> on the bay as a teenager — stealing oysters from privately owned beds and selling them to saloons — before becoming one of America's most famous writers. The preserved First and Last Chance Saloon, built in 1880, was London's regular drinking spot and looks exactly as it did when he was alive." },
{ name:"Paramount Theatre Oakland", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🎭", lat:37.8072, lon:-122.2689, cat:"Historic Theater", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/Paramount_Theatre_Oakland.jpg/320px-Paramount_Theatre_Oakland.jpg", fact:"The Paramount Theatre is one of the finest surviving examples of <em>Art Deco architecture</em> in the United States, opened in 1931 with a facade of mosaic tile and glazed terracotta that shimmers gold in afternoon light. The theater seats 3,000 people and was restored to its original glory in 1973 after a decade of abandonment." },
{ name:"Fox Theater Oakland", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🎬", lat:37.8083, lon:-122.2678, cat:"Historic Theater", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/28/Fox_Oakland_Theatre.jpg/320px-Fox_Oakland_Theatre.jpg", fact:"The Fox Theater opened in <em>1928</em> as the largest movie palace in the Bay Area, with a Moorish-inspired interior featuring a minaret rising above Broadway. After decades of neglect, it was restored and reopened in 2009 as a concert venue — the restoration revealed original hand-painted murals hidden under decades of paint." },
{ name:"Chabot Space and Science Center", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🔭", lat:37.8178, lon:-122.1817, cat:"Museum", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/Chabot_Space_and_Science_Center.jpg/320px-Chabot_Space_and_Science_Center.jpg", fact:"The Chabot Space Center sits atop the <em>Oakland hills with the darkest skies</em> accessible by public transit in the Bay Area, and its three telescopes are open to the public on Friday and Saturday nights year-round. The center's 70-foot planetarium dome is the largest in Northern California." },
{ name:"Redwood Regional Park", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🌲", lat:37.8094, lon:-122.1619, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/Redwood_Regional_Park_Oakland.jpg/320px-Redwood_Regional_Park_Oakland.jpg", fact:"Redwood Regional Park protects a grove of <em>second-growth coast redwoods</em> that grew back after the original old-growth forest was logged in the 1850s to build San Francisco — the trees are now 150 feet tall. The park's East Ridge Trail offers views of both the Golden Gate and the Sierra Nevada simultaneously on clear winter days." },
{ name:"Joaquin Miller Park", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🌲", lat:37.8019, lon:-122.1969, cat:"Historic Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/Redwood_Regional_Park_Oakland.jpg/320px-Redwood_Regional_Park_Oakland.jpg", fact:"Joaquin Miller, the <em>'Poet of the Sierras,'</em> built his hilltop estate here in the 1880s and planted most of the eucalyptus and Monterey pine trees that now define the Oakland hills landscape. Miller's self-designed funeral pyre — a concrete pyramid he wanted burned over his body — still stands in the park, unused since his family chose a conventional burial." },
{ name:"Knowland Park and Oakland Zoo", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🦒", lat:37.7528, lon:-122.1461, cat:"Park and Zoo", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/Redwood_Regional_Park_Oakland.jpg/320px-Redwood_Regional_Park_Oakland.jpg", fact:"The Oakland Zoo is built on land donated by Joseph Knowland, publisher of the <em>Oakland Tribune</em>, who purchased the hills specifically to prevent development and gave them to the city. The zoo's California Trail exhibit recreates California's pre-European ecosystems using animals — grizzly bears, condors, wolves — that were extirpated from the state within historical memory." },
{ name:"Leona Canyon Regional Open Space", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🦋", lat:37.7711, lon:-122.1594, cat:"Open Space", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/Redwood_Regional_Park_Oakland.jpg/320px-Redwood_Regional_Park_Oakland.jpg", fact:"Leona Canyon contains an <em>unusual serpentine rock outcrop</em> in the middle of Oakland's urban hills that supports a community of rare plants found nowhere else in the county, including three species of wildflowers endemic to Bay Area serpentine soils. The canyon's creek runs year-round despite being surrounded by urban development." },
{ name:"Mountain View Cemetery", county:"Alameda", emoji:"⛪", lat:37.8253, lon:-122.2344, cat:"Historic Cemetery", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ab/Mountain_View_Cemetery_Oakland.jpg/320px-Mountain_View_Cemetery_Oakland.jpg", fact:"Mountain View Cemetery, designed by Frederick Law Olmsted — designer of Central Park — in <em>1863</em>, was the first professionally designed landscape in Oakland and remains one of the finest examples of Victorian rural cemetery design in the West. Buried here are Charles Crocker and other Central Pacific Railroad magnates whose fortunes built modern California." },
{ name:"Piedmont — City of Piedmont Historic District", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🏘", lat:37.8236, lon:-122.2319, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ab/Mountain_View_Cemetery_Oakland.jpg/320px-Mountain_View_Cemetery_Oakland.jpg", fact:"Piedmont, incorporated in <em>1907</em> specifically to escape annexation by Oakland, is the most densely wealthy small city in California — a single square mile surrounded entirely by Oakland on all sides. The city has its own police, fire, and school district, funded by some of the highest property taxes per resident in the state." },
{ name:"Dunsmuir Hellman Historic Estate", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🏰", lat:37.7758, lon:-122.1736, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Dunsmuir_House_Oakland.jpg/320px-Dunsmuir_House_Oakland.jpg", fact:"The Dunsmuir Mansion, built in <em>1899</em> for coal baron Alexander Dunsmuir as a wedding gift to his mistress, was occupied for exactly one month before both newlyweds died — she from illness, he from shock. The 37-room Neoclassical mansion is now an event venue and its 50-acre grounds include one of the finest Italian formal gardens in California." },
{ name:"Peralta Adobe, San Jose Historic Site", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🏚", lat:37.7858, lon:-122.2161, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/38/Oakland_Museum_of_California.jpg/320px-Oakland_Museum_of_California.jpg", fact:"The Peralta family received the largest <em>Mexican land grant</em> in the Bay Area — 44,000 acres covering all of modern Oakland, Berkeley, Alameda, and Emeryville — as a reward for military service in 1820. The grant's boundaries were established by horseback, with the patriarch riding the perimeter and his sons following behind." },
{ name:"USS Potomac — Presidential Yacht", county:"Alameda", emoji:"⚓", lat:37.7947, lon:-122.2817, cat:"Historic Ship", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/USS_Potomac_Oakland.jpg/320px-USS_Potomac_Oakland.jpg", fact:"The USS Potomac was Franklin D. Roosevelt's <em>presidential yacht</em>, called the 'Floating White House,' where FDR held secret meetings with Winston Churchill and other world leaders during World War II. After a complex history of neglect, drug seizure, and restoration, the ship is now permanently moored at Jack London Square and open for tours." },
{ name:"Alameda — Historic Naval Air Station", county:"Alameda", emoji:"✈️", lat:37.7783, lon:-122.3097, cat:"Historic Military", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/USS_Potomac_Oakland.jpg/320px-USS_Potomac_Oakland.jpg", fact:"NAS Alameda was home to the <em>USS Hornet</em> aircraft carrier whose planes launched the Doolittle Raid on Tokyo in 1942 — the first American attack on the Japanese mainland. The base also recovered the Apollo 11 and Apollo 12 astronauts after their splashdowns — the Navy ships bringing them home docked here." },
{ name:"USS Hornet Sea, Air and Space Museum", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🚀", lat:37.7736, lon:-122.3025, cat:"Museum", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/33/USS_Hornet_museum_Alameda.jpg/320px-USS_Hornet_museum_Alameda.jpg", fact:"The USS Hornet recovered the <em>Apollo 11 and Apollo 12 astronauts</em> from the Pacific Ocean after their moon missions — the quarantine facility where Neil Armstrong was kept after returning from the moon is still aboard the ship. The carrier also served in three wars and launched the first jet aircraft to fly off a carrier deck." },
{ name:"Alameda — Victorian Architecture District", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🏘", lat:37.7652, lon:-122.2416, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/USS_Potomac_Oakland.jpg/320px-USS_Potomac_Oakland.jpg", fact:"Alameda has the highest concentration of <em>Victorian houses</em> of any city in the Bay Area — over 3,000 buildings from the 1880s and 1890s that survived because the city was bypassed by development. The island city's separation from the mainland slowed growth enough that most of its 19th-century housing stock remains intact." },
{ name:"College of Alameda — Historic Site", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🏛", lat:37.7769, lon:-122.2906, cat:"Education", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/USS_Potomac_Oakland.jpg/320px-USS_Potomac_Oakland.jpg", fact:"The College of Alameda campus sits on land that was once the primary <em>seaplane base</em> for Pan American World Airways' transpacific flying boat service in the 1930s. Pan Am's China Clipper took off from just offshore on its inaugural flight to Manila in 1935 — the first commercial transpacific air service in history." },
{ name:"Fruitvale — Historic Produce District", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🍎", lat:37.7747, lon:-122.2244, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/Fruitvale_Station_BART.jpg/320px-Fruitvale_Station_BART.jpg", fact:"Fruitvale earned its name as the <em>leading fruit-shipping district</em> in the East Bay — in the 1890s, the area's orchards produced cherries, apricots, and peaches loaded directly onto trains at the Fruitvale station. The station area is now a vibrant Latino commercial district, and its 2003 transit village was the first transit-oriented development built over a BART station." },
{ name:"San Antonio Park, Oakland", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🌳", lat:37.7869, lon:-122.2364, cat:"Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/38/Oakland_Museum_of_California.jpg/320px-Oakland_Museum_of_California.jpg", fact:"San Antonio Park sits on land that was once the <em>Mexican rancho</em> of Antonio Peralta, where longhorn cattle grazed across what is now East Oakland. The park's community garden, established in the 1970s, is one of the oldest urban community gardens in California and helped inspire the nationwide urban farming movement." },
{ name:"Estuary Park, Oakland", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🌊", lat:37.7939, lon:-122.2536, cat:"Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Jack_London_Square_Oakland.jpg/320px-Jack_London_Square_Oakland.jpg", fact:"The Oakland Estuary was once one of the <em>busiest industrial waterways</em> in the Bay Area, lined with shipyards, canneries, and warehouses that employed tens of thousands during World War II. Today's restored shoreline park built on former industrial land is one of the most dramatic examples of waterfront reclamation in California." },
{ name:"Hayward Area Historical Society Museum", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🏛", lat:37.6688, lon:-122.0808, cat:"Museum", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bc/Coyote_Hills_Regional_Park.jpg/320px-Coyote_Hills_Regional_Park.jpg", fact:"Hayward was founded in <em>1851</em> by William Hayward, who built a hotel at a crossroads that became the main supply stop for miners heading to the Sierra Nevada gold fields. The town grew as a fruit and vegetable farming center serving San Francisco — its proximity to the bay and mild climate made it the breadbasket of the East Bay for decades." },
{ name:"Hayward Fault — Observation Point", county:"Alameda", emoji:"⚡", lat:37.6583, lon:-122.0819, cat:"Geological", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bc/Coyote_Hills_Regional_Park.jpg/320px-Coyote_Hills_Regional_Park.jpg", fact:"The Hayward Fault runs directly under <em>densely populated cities</em> including Oakland, Berkeley, and Hayward, making it arguably the most dangerous fault in America. The fault is currently 'locked' — accumulating strain that scientists calculate will eventually release in a magnitude 7.0 earthquake that could kill over 800 people and damage 155,000 buildings." },
{ name:"Mission San Jose", county:"Alameda", emoji:"⛪", lat:37.5380, lon:-121.9194, cat:"Historic Mission", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8e/Mission_San_Jose_California.jpg/320px-Mission_San_Jose_California.jpg", fact:"Mission San Jose, founded in <em>1797</em>, was one of the most prosperous missions in California — its orchards, vineyards, and cattle herds supplied food to missions as far away as Santa Barbara. The mission's Ohlone converts revolted in 1828 in one of the largest Native uprisings against the mission system, under a warrior named Estanislao." },
{ name:"Ardenwood Historic Farm", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🌾", lat:37.5561, lon:-122.0336, cat:"Historic Farm", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/Ardenwood_Historic_Farm.jpg/320px-Ardenwood_Historic_Farm.jpg", fact:"Ardenwood was the <em>model farm estate</em> of George Patterson, one of California's most innovative 19th-century agriculturalists, who built a Victorian mansion overlooking his 6,000 acres of wheat. The farm now operates as a living history museum with working draft horses, heirloom crops, and costumed interpreters." },
{ name:"Coyote Hills Regional Park", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🦟", lat:37.5550, lon:-122.0811, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bc/Coyote_Hills_Regional_Park.jpg/320px-Coyote_Hills_Regional_Park.jpg", fact:"Coyote Hills contains <em>shell mounds</em> built by Ohlone people over 2,500 years — refuse heaps of clamshells, fish bones, and artifacts that grew into permanent hills rising 30 feet above the bay shore. The mounds are among the best-preserved archaeological sites in the Bay Area, offering an unbroken record of bay ecology stretching back millennia." },
{ name:"Don Edwards San Francisco Bay National Wildlife Refuge", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🦅", lat:37.5050, lon:-122.0450, cat:"Wildlife Refuge", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3b/Don_Edwards_NWR.jpg/320px-Don_Edwards_NWR.jpg", fact:"At 30,000 acres, Don Edwards is the <em>largest urban wildlife refuge in the United States</em>, protecting the last major areas of salt marsh and tidal flat on the south end of San Francisco Bay. The refuge's salt ponds — former industrial evaporation ponds turned pink by salt-loving algae — are a surreal landscape visible from commercial flights." },
{ name:"Niles Canyon Railway", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🚂", lat:37.5769, lon:-121.9808, cat:"Historic Railway", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/Niles_Canyon_Railway.jpg/320px-Niles_Canyon_Railway.jpg", fact:"The Niles Canyon line was part of the first <em>transcontinental railroad route</em> into San Francisco Bay, opened in 1869, carrying trains from Sacramento through the canyon before the Dumbarton Bridge route was completed. The canyon was also the location of Charlie Chaplin's first film studio — over 50 silent films were shot in the canyon between 1912 and 1916." },
{ name:"Fremont — Centerville Historic District", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🏘", lat:37.5489, lon:-122.0522, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/Ardenwood_Historic_Farm.jpg/320px-Ardenwood_Historic_Farm.jpg", fact:"Centerville was a prosperous farming community in the <em>1870s-1890s</em>, shipping fruit and vegetables by ferry to San Francisco from its own wharf on the bay. The area was consolidated into the new City of Fremont in 1956 — one of five towns merged into a single municipality in one of the most ambitious municipal consolidations in California history." },
{ name:"Irvington — Mission Boulevard Historic Corridor", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🛤", lat:37.5294, lon:-121.9669, cat:"Historic Route", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/Ardenwood_Historic_Farm.jpg/320px-Ardenwood_Historic_Farm.jpg", fact:"Mission Boulevard follows the route of El Camino Real — the <em>'Royal Road'</em> that connected all 21 California missions from San Diego to Sonoma, established between 1769 and 1823. The bell markers placed along the route in the 1900s are still visible at intervals, each casting-iron bell hung from a shepherd's crook post." },
{ name:"Newark Slough Wildlife Area", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🦩", lat:37.5200, lon:-122.0400, cat:"Wildlife Area", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3b/Don_Edwards_NWR.jpg/320px-Don_Edwards_NWR.jpg", fact:"Newark Slough's restored tidal wetlands are a critical nursery for <em>Dungeness crab, herring, and salmon</em> that support the commercial fishing industry of San Francisco Bay. The slough was diked and farmed for a century before restoration began in 1994 — scientists were amazed at how quickly native plants and fish returned once tidal flow was reestablished." },
{ name:"Sunol Regional Wilderness", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🦁", lat:37.5133, lon:-121.8297, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/Sunol_Regional_Wilderness.jpg/320px-Sunol_Regional_Wilderness.jpg", fact:"Sunol is the only regional park in the East Bay where <em>cattle still graze</em> as part of active rangeland management — a practice that actually improves habitat for native wildflowers and ground-nesting birds compared to ungrazed grassland. The wilderness area's Alameda Creek contains one of the last viable steelhead trout runs in the San Francisco Bay watershed." },
{ name:"Ohlone Wilderness Trail", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🥾", lat:37.5500, lon:-121.8000, cat:"Trail", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/Sunol_Regional_Wilderness.jpg/320px-Sunol_Regional_Wilderness.jpg", fact:"The 29-mile Ohlone Wilderness Trail traverses <em>four distinct ecological zones</em> — bay marsh, coastal scrub, valley grassland, and oak woodland — following ancient Native American trading paths across the Diablo Range. The trail requires a permit and a self-contained camp kit because the wilderness has no water sources for long stretches." },
{ name:"Del Valle Regional Park", county:"Alameda", emoji:"💧", lat:37.6011, lon:-121.7411, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/Sunol_Regional_Wilderness.jpg/320px-Sunol_Regional_Wilderness.jpg", fact:"Lake Del Valle, created by Arroyo Valle Dam in <em>1968</em>, provides drinking water to Livermore and Pleasanton and recreation to over a million visitors a year. The reservoir's cool, clear water supports an unusual fishery for the East Bay — rainbow and brown trout stocked for year-round angling." },
{ name:"Livermore Valley Wine Country", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🍷", lat:37.6819, lon:-121.7680, cat:"Wine Region", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a6/Altamont_Pass_Wind_Farm.jpg/320px-Altamont_Pass_Wind_Farm.jpg", fact:"The Livermore Valley has been producing wine since <em>1883</em>, making it California's oldest continuously operating wine region — older than Napa Valley's commercial wine industry. The valley's distinctive gravelly soils were brought inland from the coast by ancient rivers, and the same soil type found here gave rise to Château Pétrus in Bordeaux, France." },
{ name:"Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory", county:"Alameda", emoji:"⚛", lat:37.6892, lon:-121.7058, cat:"Research Facility", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a6/Altamont_Pass_Wind_Farm.jpg/320px-Altamont_Pass_Wind_Farm.jpg", fact:"Lawrence Livermore Lab has been designing <em>every American nuclear weapon</em> since 1952, and its National Ignition Facility achieved fusion ignition in 2022 — the first time in history that a controlled fusion reaction produced more energy than it consumed. The lab's 800-acre campus employs 8,000 scientists and is the largest employer in the Tri-Valley." },
{ name:"Tesla Road — Historic Vineyards", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🍇", lat:37.6700, lon:-121.8000, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a6/Altamont_Pass_Wind_Farm.jpg/320px-Altamont_Pass_Wind_Farm.jpg", fact:"Tesla Road is named for the now-vanished coal mining town of Tesla, which operated the largest <em>underground coal mine</em> in California from 1892 to 1914. The town's 2,000 residents evaporated overnight when the mine closed, and today the only evidence is a few depressions in the ground and a cemetery hidden in the oak woodland." },
{ name:"Pleasanton Downtown Historic District", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🏘", lat:37.6624, lon:-121.8747, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/Sunol_Regional_Wilderness.jpg/320px-Sunol_Regional_Wilderness.jpg", fact:"Pleasanton's Main Street has been continuously commercial since the <em>1860s</em> and retains the scale and character of a 19th-century California market town. The town earned the nickname 'Most Desperate Town in the West' during the 1890s for its tolerance of gambling halls and outlaws — a reputation locals now celebrate at an annual festival." },
{ name:"Shadow Cliffs Regional Recreation Area", county:"Alameda", emoji:"💧", lat:37.6567, lon:-121.8603, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/Sunol_Regional_Wilderness.jpg/320px-Sunol_Regional_Wilderness.jpg", fact:"Shadow Cliffs was created by <em>gravel dredging operations</em> that extracted sand and gravel for Bay Area construction from the 1950s through the 1980s — the excavated pits filled with groundwater to create the lake. The swimming area and waterslide are among the most popular summer recreation spots in the East Bay." },
{ name:"Altamont Pass Wind Farm", county:"Alameda", emoji:"💨", lat:37.7300, lon:-121.6500, cat:"Energy", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a6/Altamont_Pass_Wind_Farm.jpg/320px-Altamont_Pass_Wind_Farm.jpg", fact:"The Altamont Pass Wind Farm, established in <em>1981</em>, was the first large-scale wind energy project in the United States and helped establish California as the world leader in renewable energy. The 5,000 turbines generate enough electricity to power 120,000 homes — though the older-style turbines have been controversial for killing raptors, and newer designs are replacing them." },
{ name:"Berkeley Marina and Aquatic Park", county:"Alameda", emoji:"⛵", lat:37.8636, lon:-122.3172, cat:"Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2e/Lawrence_Hall_of_Science.jpg/320px-Lawrence_Hall_of_Science.jpg", fact:"The Berkeley Marina was built on <em>900 acres of landfill</em> created from the city's garbage over 40 years — the mounds of the former landfill are still visible as hills in Cesar Chavez Park. The marina's constant afternoon winds have made it one of the best locations in the Bay Area for kite flying, with the Berkeley Kite Festival drawing 50,000 people each year." },
{ name:"UC Berkeley — Sather Tower (Campanile)", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🏛", lat:37.8724, lon:-122.2595, cat:"University Landmark", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6b/Campanile_UC_Berkeley.jpg/320px-Campanile_UC_Berkeley.jpg", fact:"Sather Tower, modeled after the <em>Campanile di San Marco</em> in Venice and completed in 1914, stands 307 feet tall and houses a 61-bell carillon played by students three times daily. The tower's observation deck offers a 360-degree view that on clear days extends from the Farallon Islands to the Sierra Nevada — a 200-mile panorama." },
{ name:"UC Berkeley — Lawrence Hall of Science", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🔬", lat:37.8795, lon:-122.2472, cat:"Museum", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2e/Lawrence_Hall_of_Science.jpg/320px-Lawrence_Hall_of_Science.jpg", fact:"Lawrence Hall of Science sits on the Berkeley hills above campus and was the first science museum in the United States designed as a <em>public learning laboratory</em> rather than a display institution — visitors are encouraged to conduct real experiments. The building's rooftop terrace offers one of the best views of the Bay Area available to the public." },
{ name:"Tilden Regional Park", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🌿", lat:37.8944, lon:-122.2428, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8d/Tilden_Regional_Park_merry_go_round.jpg/320px-Tilden_Regional_Park_merry_go_round.jpg", fact:"Tilden Park's <em>steam train, antique carousel, and botanical garden</em> were built during the Depression by unemployed workers through the Civil Conservation Corps — and all three still operate today. The park's Brazilian Room, a redwood pavilion built in 1938, was a gift from Brazil to California and has hosted dances, weddings, and concerts for 85 years." },
{ name:"Claremont Hotel and Spa", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🏨", lat:37.8589, lon:-122.2428, cat:"Historic Hotel", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/Claremont_Resort_Berkeley_Hills.jpg/320px-Claremont_Resort_Berkeley_Hills.jpg", fact:"The Claremont Hotel, opened in <em>1915</em>, is one of the most recognizable landmarks on the Bay Area skyline — its white towers visible from San Francisco across the bay. The hotel sits exactly on the Hayward Fault; the fault line runs under the tennis courts, and a painted stripe on the court marks where the two sides have moved relative to each other over decades." },
{ name:"Emeryville Shellmound Site", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🏺", lat:37.8333, lon:-122.2906, cat:"Archaeological Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/38/Oakland_Museum_of_California.jpg/320px-Oakland_Museum_of_California.jpg", fact:"The Emeryville Shellmound was the <em>largest and oldest shell mound</em> in the Bay Area — a 60-foot-high mound of oyster shells, human burials, and artifacts accumulated by Ohlone people over 3,500 years. The mound was completely destroyed in 1924 to build a paint factory, and the area is now a shopping mall — one of the most significant archaeological sites in California lost to development." },
{ name:"Oakland Chinatown", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🏮", lat:37.7969, lon:-122.2697, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3b/Oakland_Chinatown.jpg/320px-Oakland_Chinatown.jpg", fact:"Oakland Chinatown, established in <em>1852</em>, is older than San Francisco's Chinatown and has been continuously inhabited by Chinese Americans for over 170 years. When San Francisco's Chinatown was destroyed in the 1906 earthquake and fire, thousands of refugees moved to Oakland — tripling the district's size almost overnight." },
{ name:"Fruitvale Station Memorial", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🕯", lat:37.7747, lon:-122.2244, cat:"Memorial", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/Fruitvale_Station_BART.jpg/320px-Fruitvale_Station_BART.jpg", fact:"Fruitvale BART Station was the site of the <em>2009 shooting of Oscar Grant</em> by a transit police officer, an event that sparked international protests about police violence against Black Americans and inspired the film Fruitvale Station. The station's plaza is now a community gathering place with murals memorializing Grant and others lost to police violence." },
{ name:"San Leandro Bay Regional Shoreline", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🌊", lat:37.7381, lon:-122.2050, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/Fruitvale_Station_BART.jpg/320px-Fruitvale_Station_BART.jpg", fact:"San Leandro Bay was once the most <em>productive shellfish habitat</em> in the East Bay, with oyster beds covering hundreds of acres that fed thousands of Ohlone people for millennia. The bay was filled with industrial waste and garbage through the mid-20th century; today restored wetlands at the shoreline park support hundreds of thousands of shorebirds." },
{ name:"San Leandro Heritage Park", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🏚", lat:37.7219, lon:-122.1561, cat:"Historic Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/Fruitvale_Station_BART.jpg/320px-Fruitvale_Station_BART.jpg", fact:"San Leandro Heritage Park contains the <em>1878 Estudillo House</em>, built by the family who received one of the original Mexican land grants covering much of the East Bay. The house's hand-hewn redwood frame was cut from the Berkeley hills, and the basement still contains the original wine cellar where the family stored homemade wine from their vineyard." },
{ name:"Oakland Coliseum", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🏟", lat:37.7516, lon:-122.2005, cat:"Stadium", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Oakland-Alameda_County_Coliseum.jpg/320px-Oakland-Alameda_County_Coliseum.jpg", fact:"The Oakland Coliseum, opened in <em>1966</em>, was for decades home to three major professional sports teams simultaneously — a distinction shared only by Madison Square Garden. The stadium's 'Mount Davis' luxury seating addition, built for the 1995 Raiders return, permanently blocked the mountain view that gave the original stadium its character." },
{ name:"Mills College — Historic Campus", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🏛", lat:37.7908, lon:-122.1883, cat:"Historic Campus", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/38/Oakland_Museum_of_California.jpg/320px-Oakland_Museum_of_California.jpg", fact:"Mills College, founded in <em>1852</em>, is the oldest women's college west of the Rockies and its 135-acre campus contains the finest collection of Arts and Crafts architecture in the East Bay. When trustees voted to admit men in 1990, students organized a two-week strike that became national news — the board reversed the decision within days." },
{ name:"Knowland Family Historic Site", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🌿", lat:37.7528, lon:-122.1461, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/Redwood_Regional_Park_Oakland.jpg/320px-Redwood_Regional_Park_Oakland.jpg", fact:"Joseph Knowland purchased the <em>Leona Heights hills</em> in the 1920s specifically to prevent their development, donating them to the City of Oakland as parkland. His son William served as U.S. Senator and ran unsuccessfully for Governor of California in 1958 — a loss that effectively ended the family's century of political dominance in Alameda County." },
{ name:"Chabot Canal — Historic Water System", county:"Alameda", emoji:"💧", lat:37.8150, lon:-122.1800, cat:"Historic Infrastructure", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/Redwood_Regional_Park_Oakland.jpg/320px-Redwood_Regional_Park_Oakland.jpg", fact:"Anthony Chabot built the <em>first piped water system</em> in the East Bay in 1875, constructing Lake Chabot and a gravity-fed pipeline to deliver water to Oakland — a project completed without any government funding, financed entirely by private capital. Chabot's engineering marvel is still operational today, over 140 years after it was built." },
{ name:"Pleasanton Ridge Regional Park", county:"Alameda", emoji:"🦌", lat:37.6278, lon:-121.9333, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/Sunol_Regional_Wilderness.jpg/320px-Sunol_Regional_Wilderness.jpg", fact:"Pleasanton Ridge offers the <em>best unobstructed views</em> of the Livermore Valley wine country from above, with rows of vineyards visible stretching to the horizon. The ridge is crossed by the Contra Costa-Alameda county line, and the geological boundary between two different rock formations follows almost exactly the same line." },

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════
// SAN FRANCISCO COUNTY
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════

{ name:"Golden Gate Bridge", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🌉", lat:37.8199, lon:-122.4783, cat:"Landmark", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/GoldenGateBridge-001.jpg/320px-GoldenGateBridge-001.jpg", fact:"When it opened in <em>1937</em>, the Golden Gate Bridge was the longest suspension bridge in the world, and its distinctive International Orange color was originally just a primer coat that the architect loved so much he made it permanent. The bridge's towers flex up to 16 feet in high winds, and the entire bridge expands and contracts nearly a foot with temperature changes." },
{ name:"Alcatraz Island", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🏝", lat:37.8270, lon:-122.4230, cat:"Historic Prison", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0a/Alcatraz_Island_as_seen_from_above.jpg/320px-Alcatraz_Island_as_seen_from_above.jpg", fact:"Alcatraz held some of America's most notorious criminals including Al Capone and Machine Gun Kelly, but the <em>27-year federal prison era</em> is relatively recent — the island served as a military fort and prison for 80 years before that. In 1969, Native American activists occupied Alcatraz for 19 months under the 'Indians of All Tribes' movement, a landmark event in the American Indian rights movement." },
{ name:"Fisherman's Wharf", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🦀", lat:37.8080, lon:-122.4177, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7d/Fishermans_Wharf_SF.jpg/320px-Fishermans_Wharf_SF.jpg", fact:"Fisherman's Wharf developed in the <em>1850s</em> when Italian immigrant fishermen, primarily from Genoa and Sicily, established a crab and shrimp fishing community along the northern waterfront. The Dungeness crab, still central to the wharf's identity, has been harvested in San Francisco Bay since the Gold Rush." },
{ name:"Coit Tower", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🗼", lat:37.8024, lon:-122.4058, cat:"Landmark", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/08/Coit_Tower%2C_SF.jpg/320px-Coit_Tower%2C_SF.jpg", fact:"Coit Tower was built in <em>1933</em> with a bequest from eccentric socialite Lillie Hitchcock Coit, who was obsessed with San Francisco's fire department and left money specifically for a monument to firefighters. The tower's interior murals, painted by 25 artists during the Depression, caused a near-scandal for their communist imagery — the city tried to paint them over before public outrage stopped them." },
{ name:"Lombard Street", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🌺", lat:37.8021, lon:-122.4186, cat:"Landmark", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/Lombard_street_in_SF_4.jpg/320px-Lombard_street_in_SF_4.jpg", fact:"Lombard Street's famous eight hairpin turns were added in <em>1922</em> to reduce the grade of a block that was simply too steep to drive straight — before the curves, only horse-drawn vehicles could navigate it. The block's hydrangeas are replanted every year by city workers, and residents of the street have periodically campaigned to charge admission to tourists." },
{ name:"Painted Ladies — Alamo Square", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🏘", lat:37.7762, lon:-122.4330, cat:"Historic Buildings", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8d/Painted_Ladies_San_Francisco_with_skyline.jpg/320px-Painted_Ladies_San_Francisco_with_skyline.jpg", fact:"The 'Painted Ladies' Victorian row houses facing Alamo Square were built in the <em>1890s</em> as middle-class housing and survived the 1906 earthquake because the fire that consumed downtown never reached this neighborhood. The houses' elaborate paint schemes are a modern innovation — Victorian San Franciscans actually considered bright paint in poor taste and used muted earth tones." },
{ name:"Haight-Ashbury Historic District", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"☮", lat:37.7692, lon:-122.4481, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/Haight-Ashbury_street_sign.jpg/320px-Haight-Ashbury_street_sign.jpg", fact:"The Haight-Ashbury district became the epicenter of the <em>1967 Summer of Love</em>, when an estimated 100,000 young people converged on the neighborhood — overwhelming the city's infrastructure and establishing the hippie counterculture as a national phenomenon. The intersection of Haight and Ashbury Streets still draws tourists, though the neighborhood is now among San Francisco's most expensive." },
{ name:"Castro District", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🏳️‍🌈", lat:37.7609, lon:-122.4350, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/73/Castro_district_san_francisco.jpg/320px-Castro_district_san_francisco.jpg", fact:"The Castro became the <em>world's first openly gay neighborhood</em> in the early 1970s, when Harvey Milk established his camera shop and political base on Castro Street. Milk's 1978 assassination by fellow supervisor Dan White, and the subsequent lenient manslaughter verdict, sparked the White Night Riots — events that galvanized the modern LGBT rights movement." },
{ name:"Mission Dolores", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"⛪", lat:37.7651, lon:-122.4269, cat:"Historic Mission", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f5/Mission_Dolores_Basilica.jpg/320px-Mission_Dolores_Basilica.jpg", fact:"Mission Dolores, founded in <em>1776</em> — just five days before the signing of the Declaration of Independence — is the oldest intact building in San Francisco and survived the 1906 earthquake while the adjacent basilica was destroyed. The mission cemetery contains the graves of over 5,000 Ohlone people who died of disease after conversion." },
{ name:"Sutro Baths Ruins", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🌊", lat:37.7800, lon:-122.5133, cat:"Historic Ruins", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Sutro_Baths.jpg/320px-Sutro_Baths.jpg", fact:"Sutro Baths, opened in <em>1896</em>, was the world's largest indoor swimming complex — six glass-enclosed saltwater pools holding nearly 2 million gallons. The baths could accommodate 10,000 visitors simultaneously, but were never commercially successful; they burned in 1966 while being demolished for apartments, and their concrete ruins now sit in Golden Gate National Recreation Area." },
{ name:"Cliff House", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🏠", lat:37.7786, lon:-122.5133, cat:"Historic Building", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Cliff_House_2018.jpg/320px-Cliff_House_2018.jpg", fact:"Three successive Cliff Houses have stood on this dramatic oceanfront bluff since <em>1863</em>, each one destroyed by fire, storm, or earthquake. The current building, dating to 1909, survived by being owned by Adolph Sutro, who rebuilt it in fireproof concrete after two earlier wooden structures burned — the ruins of the original Sutro Baths lie just below." },
{ name:"Land's End Trail", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🌊", lat:37.7833, lon:-122.5119, cat:"Trail", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Cliff_House_2018.jpg/320px-Cliff_House_2018.jpg", fact:"Land's End sits on the most treacherous stretch of the California coast north of Point Conception — over <em>200 ships have wrecked</em> on the rocks offshore since the Gold Rush, and ribs of wooden hulls are still visible at low tide. The trail hugs the cliff face through cypress groves planted by the same Adolph Sutro who built the Cliff House." },
{ name:"Baker Beach", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🏖", lat:37.7936, lon:-122.4836, cat:"Beach", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5e/Baker_Beach_San_Francisco.jpg/320px-Baker_Beach_San_Francisco.jpg", fact:"Baker Beach was the <em>birthplace of Burning Man</em> in 1986, when a small group built and burned a wooden figure on the sand — the event moved to the Black Rock Desert in Nevada after it outgrew the beach. The beach's northern end is clothing-optional and offers one of the most dramatic views of the Golden Gate Bridge from below." },
{ name:"Fort Point National Historic Site", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🏰", lat:37.8103, lon:-122.4772, cat:"Historic Fort", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/Fort_Point_from_Golden_Gate_Bridge.jpg/320px-Fort_Point_from_Golden_Gate_Bridge.jpg", fact:"Fort Point, completed in <em>1861</em>, was a masterpiece of pre-Civil War military engineering — its 5-foot-thick brick walls were designed to withstand cannon fire and house 500 soldiers. When Strauss designed the Golden Gate Bridge, he built an arch over the fort to preserve it rather than demolish it, a decision that now allows visitors to stand beneath the bridge's south anchorage." },
{ name:"Presidio of San Francisco", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🌲", lat:37.7983, lon:-122.4544, cat:"Historic Military", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/Presidio_of_San_Francisco.jpg/320px-Presidio_of_San_Francisco.jpg", fact:"The Presidio has been continuously operated as a military base since <em>1776</em> — first by Spain, then Mexico, then the United States — making it the oldest military installation in the American West by over 70 years. When the army left in 1994, it was transferred to the National Park Service and became a national park within a city, with residents paying market-rate rent to live inside." },
{ name:"Crissy Field", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🌊", lat:37.8047, lon:-122.4661, cat:"Historic Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ce/Crissy_Field_restored_tidal_marsh.jpg/320px-Crissy_Field_restored_tidal_marsh.jpg", fact:"Crissy Field was one of the most significant <em>early aviation sites</em> in the West — the Army's first air station on the Pacific Coast, where pilots trained for World War I and early air mail routes were inaugurated. The field was paved over as a parking lot in the 1970s before a massive restoration project in 2001 removed the asphalt and restored a mile of tidal marsh." },
{ name:"Palace of Fine Arts", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🏛", lat:37.8031, lon:-122.4483, cat:"Historic Building", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5e/Palace_of_Fine_Arts_San_Francisco.jpg/320px-Palace_of_Fine_Arts_San_Francisco.jpg", fact:"The Palace of Fine Arts was built as a <em>temporary structure</em> for the 1915 Panama-Pacific International Exposition out of plaster and burlap — and was never demolished because San Franciscans loved it too much. The building slowly crumbled for 50 years until a complete reconstruction in concrete in the 1960s, and again in the 2000s." },
{ name:"Ghirardelli Square", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🍫", lat:37.8058, lon:-122.4228, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/Ghirardelli_Square_SF.jpg/320px-Ghirardelli_Square_SF.jpg", fact:"Ghirardelli Square was the first major <em>adaptive reuse of an industrial building</em> in American history — a defunct chocolate factory transformed into a retail complex in 1964, pioneering a form of urban development that is now common worldwide. Domingo Ghirardelli started making chocolate in the building in 1852, and the factory produced chocolate continuously until 1962." },
{ name:"Transamerica Pyramid", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🏢", lat:37.7952, lon:-122.4028, cat:"Landmark", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/Transamerica_Pyramid_San_Francisco.jpg/320px-Transamerica_Pyramid_San_Francisco.jpg", fact:"The Transamerica Pyramid, completed in <em>1972</em>, was deeply controversial when proposed — San Franciscans called it a 'dunce cap' and fought its construction for years. The building's unusual shape is actually a sophisticated structural solution: the tapered form reduces wind load at upper floors by 40% compared to a conventional skyscraper, making it more earthquake-resistant." },
{ name:"Ferry Building", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"⛴", lat:37.7956, lon:-122.3935, cat:"Historic Building", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/72/San_Francisco_Ferry_Building.jpg/320px-San_Francisco_Ferry_Building.jpg", fact:"The Ferry Building, opened in <em>1898</em>, processed 50 million passengers a year at its peak — the second busiest transit terminal in the world after Charing Cross in London — when it was the hub of the ferry system that was the Bay Area's only cross-bay transit. After the Bay Bridge opened in 1936, ferry use collapsed and the building was used as an office building, its famous clock tower hidden behind a freeway for 50 years." },
{ name:"Embarcadero Historic Seawall", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🌊", lat:37.8000, lon:-122.3950, cat:"Historic Infrastructure", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5f/Embarcadero_San_Francisco.jpg/320px-Embarcadero_San_Francisco.jpg", fact:"The Embarcadero seawall was built between <em>1878 and 1916</em> by filling the bay with rubble from the city's many hills, extending the shoreline a quarter mile into the water. The 3-mile seawall is now dangerously undermined by liquefaction risk in earthquakes — the city is undertaking a $5 billion project to rebuild it before the next major quake." },
{ name:"Chinatown, San Francisco", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🏮", lat:37.7941, lon:-122.4078, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e5/Chinatown_San_Francisco.jpg/320px-Chinatown_San_Francisco.jpg", fact:"San Francisco's Chinatown, established in <em>1848</em>, is the oldest in North America and one of the most densely populated urban neighborhoods in the United States. After the 1906 earthquake destroyed it completely, city officials tried to relocate Chinatown to the industrial waterfront — the Chinese community rebuilt on the original site so quickly that their plan was thwarted within weeks." },
{ name:"North Beach — City Lights Bookstore", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"📚", lat:37.7975, lon:-122.4067, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/City_Lights_Booksellers.jpg/320px-City_Lights_Booksellers.jpg", fact:"City Lights Bookstore, opened by poet Lawrence Ferlinghetti in <em>1953</em>, was the first all-paperback bookstore in the United States and the heart of the Beat Generation literary movement. Ferlinghetti was arrested in 1956 for publishing Allen Ginsberg's 'Howl' on obscenity charges — his acquittal established a landmark precedent for freedom of literary expression." },
{ name:"Telegraph Hill and Parrots", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🦜", lat:37.8024, lon:-122.4058, cat:"Natural Landmark", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/Coit_Tower_San_Francisco.jpg/320px-Coit_Tower_San_Francisco.jpg", fact:"Telegraph Hill is home to a wild flock of <em>50 cherry-headed conures</em> — South American parrots whose ancestors were released or escaped in the 1980s and established a self-sustaining wild population. The parrots became famous through the 2003 documentary 'The Wild Parrots of Telegraph Hill' and are now considered an unofficial city symbol." },
{ name:"Nob Hill Historic District", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🏰", lat:37.7930, lon:-122.4161, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Nob_Hill_San_Francisco.jpg/320px-Nob_Hill_San_Francisco.jpg", fact:"Nob Hill earned its name from the <em>nabobs</em> — the Big Four railroad tycoons Crocker, Hopkins, Huntington, and Stanford — who built their palatial mansions on the hill in the 1870s, reachable only after the cable car was invented. All four mansions were destroyed in the 1906 earthquake and fire; their sites are now occupied by the Fairmont and Mark Hopkins hotels." },
{ name:"Twin Peaks", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🏔", lat:37.7527, lon:-122.4477, cat:"Natural Landmark", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Twin_Peaks_San_Francisco.jpg/320px-Twin_Peaks_San_Francisco.jpg", fact:"Twin Peaks, rising 922 feet above sea level, offers the most <em>panoramic unobstructed view</em> of San Francisco from within the city limits — a 360-degree sweep from the bay to the ocean. The two peaks were called 'Los Pechos de la Chola' by the Spanish — a descriptive name that early American settlers hastily replaced with the more neutral 'Twin Peaks.'" },
{ name:"Dolores Park", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🌳", lat:37.7596, lon:-122.4269, cat:"Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e5/Dolores_Park_San_Francisco.jpg/320px-Dolores_Park_San_Francisco.jpg", fact:"Dolores Park served as a <em>refugee camp</em> for 1,606 survivors of the 1906 earthquake for nearly two years — the largest of several refugee villages established across the city. The park's two small lakes were dug in the 1870s as reservoirs, and the water they held was critical in stopping the fire that consumed the Mission District after the earthquake." },
{ name:"Cow Hollow — Octagon House", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🏠", lat:37.7983, lon:-122.4347, cat:"Historic Building", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Palace_of_Fine_Arts_MC.jpg/320px-Palace_of_Fine_Arts_MC.jpg", fact:"The Octagon House, built in <em>1861</em>, is one of only two surviving octagonal houses in San Francisco from a brief nationwide architectural fad based on the theory that eight-sided homes captured more sunlight and were healthier to live in. The fad's proponent, Orson Squire Fowler, published a 1848 book arguing that round houses had spiritual superiority over square ones." },
{ name:"Sutro Forest — Mount Sutro", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🌲", lat:37.7633, lon:-122.4561, cat:"Forest", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Cliff_House_2018.jpg/320px-Cliff_House_2018.jpg", fact:"Mount Sutro's 61-acre eucalyptus forest was planted in the <em>1880s</em> by Adolph Sutro as a private estate and urban lung for San Francisco — the forest is now so dense that its interior resembles a temperate rainforest, with almost no sunlight reaching the ground. The forest is controversial today as the non-native eucalyptus trees shade out native plants, and proposals to cut them trigger fierce community opposition." },
{ name:"Divisadero Street — Historic Corridor", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🛤", lat:37.7764, lon:-122.4378, cat:"Historic Street", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/Haight-Ashbury_street_sign.jpg/320px-Haight-Ashbury_street_sign.jpg", fact:"Divisadero Street marks the original <em>western boundary of San Francisco</em> — the Spanish word means 'dividing line' — beyond which the city did not extend until the 1880s. The street runs in a perfectly straight line from bay to ocean, bisecting the city across its widest point, and was laid out by Jasper O'Farrell in his famous 1847 street grid." },
{ name:"SoMa — South of Market Historic District", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🏭", lat:37.7785, lon:-122.4056, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/Transamerica_Pyramid_San_Francisco.jpg/320px-Transamerica_Pyramid_San_Francisco.jpg", fact:"South of Market was the <em>working-class heart of Gold Rush San Francisco</em> — a district of boarding houses, factories, and small businesses that housed the laborers who built the city. The district was almost entirely destroyed in the 1906 earthquake and fire, as its shallow sand-filled ground amplified the shaking and made fires impossible to fight." },
{ name:"Rincon Hill — Historic Neighborhood", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🏠", lat:37.7844, lon:-122.3927, cat:"Historic Neighborhood", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5f/Embarcadero_San_Francisco.jpg/320px-Embarcadero_San_Francisco.jpg", fact:"Rincon Hill was <em>San Francisco's most fashionable address</em> in the 1850s and 1860s, home to merchants and shipping magnates who built elaborate Italianate mansions on its summit. The hill was literally cut in half in 1869 to make Second Street grade easier — the fill was used to extend the waterfront — and the neighborhood never recovered its social status." },
{ name:"Potrero Hill — Civil War Era Shipyard Site", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"⚓", lat:37.7594, lon:-122.4003, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Bernal_Heights_Park.jpg/320px-Bernal_Heights_Park.jpg", fact:"The Potrero Hill shipyards built <em>wooden sailing ships</em> for the Pacific trade from the 1850s through the 1880s, when the neighborhood was the industrial heart of San Francisco. The hill's naturally sheltered position from bay winds and proximity to the waterfront made it ideal for heavy industry that has now been replaced by tech offices and restaurants." },
{ name:"Bernal Heights Park", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🌄", lat:37.7425, lon:-122.4161, cat:"Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Bernal_Heights_Park.jpg/320px-Bernal_Heights_Park.jpg", fact:"Bernal Heights summit offers <em>360-degree views</em> of the entire San Francisco peninsula, including a rare angle showing the bay, ocean, and all the city's major hills simultaneously. The hill's name comes from Californio soldier Joaquin Bernal, who grazed cattle here under a Mexican land grant in the 1820s." },
{ name:"Glen Canyon Park", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🌿", lat:37.7394, lon:-122.4442, cat:"Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Twin_Peaks_San_Francisco.jpg/320px-Twin_Peaks_San_Francisco.jpg", fact:"Glen Canyon is a <em>hidden natural gorge</em> in the middle of San Francisco — a 70-foot-deep canyon with a year-round creek and coastal scrub ecosystem surrounded on all sides by the city. The canyon's Islais Creek is one of the last free-flowing streams in San Francisco; all other creeks have been buried in underground pipes." },
{ name:"Ocean Beach", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🏄", lat:37.7594, lon:-122.5103, cat:"Beach", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f9/Ocean_Beach_San_Francisco.jpg/320px-Ocean_Beach_San_Francisco.jpg", fact:"Ocean Beach stretches for <em>3.5 miles</em> along the western edge of San Francisco and has the most powerful and dangerous surf on the California coast north of Santa Cruz — rip currents, sneaker waves, and cold water make swimming extremely hazardous. The beach has been the site of over 100 shipwrecks, and buried hulls regularly emerge after major storms erode the sand." },
{ name:"San Francisco Botanical Garden", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🌸", lat:37.7671, lon:-122.4683, cat:"Botanical Garden", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3f/San_Francisco_Botanical_Garden.jpg/320px-San_Francisco_Botanical_Garden.jpg", fact:"The San Francisco Botanical Garden contains the <em>finest collection of Chilean and New Zealand plants</em> in the Northern Hemisphere, thriving in San Francisco's fog climate that mimics their native conditions. The garden's ancient plant collection includes dawn redwoods and cycads — species unchanged from specimens found in 100-million-year-old fossils." },
{ name:"Japanese Tea Garden, Golden Gate Park", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🌸", lat:37.7705, lon:-122.4699, cat:"Historic Garden", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2b/San_Francisco_Japanese_Tea_Garden_2013.JPG/320px-San_Francisco_Japanese_Tea_Garden_2013.JPG", fact:"The Japanese Tea Garden, established in <em>1894</em> for the California Midwinter International Exposition, is the oldest public Japanese garden in the United States. The fortune cookie was invented here by the garden's Japanese-American curator Makoto Hagiwara in the 1890s — a fact disputed by a Los Angeles restaurant in a good-natured ongoing feud." },
{ name:"de Young Museum", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🎨", lat:37.7714, lon:-122.4686, cat:"Museum", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/De_Young_Museum_San_Francisco.jpg/320px-De_Young_Museum_San_Francisco.jpg", fact:"The de Young Museum's <em>copper-clad tower</em> is designed to oxidize and match the surrounding trees of Golden Gate Park over decades — a building that literally changes color as it ages. The museum was destroyed in the 1906 earthquake, rebuilt and destroyed again in the 1989 earthquake, and the current building opened in 2005 with a foundation system that can withstand a magnitude 8.0 quake." },
{ name:"Conservatory of Flowers", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🌺", lat:37.7729, lon:-122.4600, cat:"Historic Building", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6b/San_Francisco_Conservatory_of_Flowers.jpg/320px-San_Francisco_Conservatory_of_Flowers.jpg", fact:"The Conservatory of Flowers, opened in <em>1879</em>, is the oldest existing public wood-and-glass conservatory in the Western Hemisphere — its design was copied from the great greenhouse at Kew Gardens in London. The Victorian greenhouse was badly damaged in a 1995 windstorm and closed for eight years of restoration before reopening in 2003 with its historic collection of tropical plants intact." },
{ name:"Panhandle — Historic Squatters Community", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🌳", lat:37.7722, lon:-122.4483, cat:"Historic Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/Haight-Ashbury_street_sign.jpg/320px-Haight-Ashbury_street_sign.jpg", fact:"The Panhandle was created when the city extended Golden Gate Park eastward to connect with downtown, and the strip of park was controversially carved through an <em>established working-class neighborhood</em> in the 1870s. During the Summer of Love in 1967, the Panhandle's free concerts organized by the Grateful Dead and Jefferson Airplane attracted crowds of thousands." },
{ name:"Kezar Stadium", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🏟", lat:37.7669, lon:-122.4561, cat:"Historic Stadium", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f7/Kezar_Stadium_SF.jpg/320px-Kezar_Stadium_SF.jpg", fact:"Kezar Stadium, opened in <em>1925</em>, was home to the San Francisco 49ers for their first 26 seasons and hosted the Beatles during their final concert tour in 1966. The intimate 10,000-seat stadium that replaced the original 59,000-seat bowl is still used for high school football and amateur events — its location at the corner of Golden Gate Park makes it one of the most beautiful urban stadiums in the country." },
{ name:"Buena Vista Park", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🌳", lat:37.7706, lon:-122.4416, cat:"Historic Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/Haight-Ashbury_street_sign.jpg/320px-Haight-Ashbury_street_sign.jpg", fact:"Buena Vista Park, established in <em>1867</em>, is the oldest official park in San Francisco and its hillside paths were laid out by Frederick Law Olmsted. The park's summit at 569 feet offers a panoramic view of downtown, the bay, and the ocean, and its dense tree canopy creates a microclimate that can be 10 degrees cooler than the surrounding streets on sunny days." },
{ name:"Corona Heights Park — Randall Museum", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🦎", lat:37.7647, lon:-122.4383, cat:"Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/73/Castro_district_san_francisco.jpg/320px-Castro_district_san_francisco.jpg", fact:"Corona Heights' exposed red chert outcroppings are <em>200 million years old</em> — ancient seafloor scraped off the Pacific Plate and plastered onto the North American continent as oceanic crust subducted. The Randall Museum's live animal collection, a neighborhood institution for 75 years, features native California species in an intimate, hands-on setting." },
{ name:"Seward Street Slides", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🛝", lat:37.7586, lon:-122.4431, cat:"Recreation", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/73/Castro_district_san_francisco.jpg/320px-Castro_district_san_francisco.jpg", fact:"The Seward Street slides are <em>concrete slides built into a hillside</em> in the 1970s that have been a neighborhood secret for 50 years — visitors must bring their own cardboard to slide on, and the friction-worn concrete provides a remarkably fast ride. The slides were threatened with demolition several times but neighborhood pressure kept them open." },
{ name:"Dolores Street Historic Palms", county:"San Francisco", emoji:"🌴", lat:37.7651, lon:-122.4269, cat:"Street", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e5/Dolores_Park_San_Francisco.jpg/320px-Dolores_Park_San_Francisco.jpg", fact:"Dolores Street's <em>row of mature Canary Island date palms</em>, planted in the 1910s, is the longest continuous palm tree boulevard in San Francisco and frames one of the city's most photographed views, with the Mission Dolores campanile in the background. The palms were threatened by a street widening project in the 1960s; neighbors chained themselves to the trees to save them." },

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════
// MARIN COUNTY
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════

{ name:"Point Reyes National Seashore", county:"Marin", emoji:"🌊", lat:38.0599, lon:-122.8742, cat:"National Seashore", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/Point_Reyes_National_Seashore.jpg/320px-Point_Reyes_National_Seashore.jpg", fact:"Point Reyes Peninsula sits on the <em>Pacific Plate</em> and is geologically moving northwest at 2 inches per year — during the 1906 earthquake, it lurched 20 feet northward in a single instant, offsetting fence lines that are still visible today. The seashore protects the southernmost breeding colony of elephant seals on the California coast, with over 2,000 animals hauling out on Drakes Beach each winter." },
{ name:"Mount Tamalpais", county:"Marin", emoji:"🏔", lat:37.9238, lon:-122.5969, cat:"Mountain", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Mount_Tamalpais_West_Peak.jpg/320px-Mount_Tamalpais_West_Peak.jpg", fact:"Mount Tamalpais is the birthplace of <em>mountain biking</em> — in the late 1970s, a group of cyclists began riding converted cruiser bikes down its fire roads, a practice that evolved into a global sport. The mountain's 2,571-foot summit offers views of 7 of the San Francisco Bay Area's 9 counties on clear days." },
{ name:"Muir Woods National Monument", county:"Marin", emoji:"🌲", lat:37.8914, lon:-122.5808, cat:"National Monument", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Muir_woods_cathedral_grove.jpg/320px-Muir_woods_cathedral_grove.jpg", fact:"Muir Woods contains the <em>closest old-growth coast redwood grove</em> to a major metropolitan area in the world — trees up to 1,200 years old grow just 12 miles from downtown San Francisco. The monument was created in 1908 when Congressman William Kent donated the land to prevent its logging, and President Roosevelt named it after John Muir over Kent's objections." },
{ name:"Sausalito Waterfront Historic District", county:"Marin", emoji:"⛵", lat:37.8591, lon:-122.4852, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Sausalito_waterfront.jpg/320px-Sausalito_waterfront.jpg", fact:"Sausalito's houseboats, now among the most expensive floating homes in the world, began as <em>improvised shelters for World War II shipyard workers</em> who couldn't find affordable housing on land. The houseboat community fought a famous battle against city authorities in the 1970s — the 'Houseboat Wars' — that ended in a negotiated settlement allowing the boats to remain." },
{ name:"Bay Model Visitor Center, Sausalito", county:"Marin", emoji:"🌊", lat:37.8736, lon:-122.5022, cat:"Museum", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/Bay_Model_Visitor_Center.jpg/320px-Bay_Model_Visitor_Center.jpg", fact:"The Bay Model is a <em>1.5-acre hydraulic scale model</em> of San Francisco Bay and the Sacramento-San Joaquin Delta, built by the Army Corps of Engineers in 1956 to study how proposed projects would affect bay tides and currents. The model predicted that a proposed freshwater dam across the bay would create a shallow, stagnant swamp — a finding that killed the project and helped inspire the modern bay conservation movement." },
{ name:"Tiburon Historic Downtown", county:"Marin", emoji:"🏘", lat:37.8908, lon:-122.4561, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/46/Tiburon_California.jpg/320px-Tiburon_California.jpg", fact:"Tiburon's Main Street is built on <em>railroad car barges</em> that were permanently beached along the waterfront in the early 1900s — the historic buildings along the water are actually sitting on the hulls of converted ferry barges. The railroad terminal here was the transfer point where transcontinental trains from the east were loaded onto ferries to cross the bay to San Francisco." },
{ name:"Angel Island State Park", county:"Marin", emoji:"🏝", lat:37.8608, lon:-122.4317, cat:"State Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f7/Angel_Island_aerial.jpg/320px-Angel_Island_aerial.jpg", fact:"Angel Island served as the '<em>Ellis Island of the West</em>' from 1910 to 1940, processing 1 million immigrants — mostly from China, Japan, and the Philippines — who were detained for days, months, or years while their cases were reviewed. Chinese detainees carved over 200 poems into the walls of the detention barracks, discovered during restoration in 1970." },
{ name:"Stinson Beach", county:"Marin", emoji:"🏖", lat:37.9019, lon:-122.6419, cat:"Beach", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f7/Stinson_Beach_CA.jpg/320px-Stinson_Beach_CA.jpg", fact:"Stinson Beach is the <em>warmest swimming beach</em> accessible from San Francisco, sheltered from prevailing winds by the bulk of Mount Tamalpais which blocks the afternoon fog. The beach gained national attention when a great white shark attack in 1981 — the first fatality at Stinson Beach — inspired increased shark research that fundamentally changed our understanding of white shark behavior." },
{ name:"Bolinas Lagoon", county:"Marin", emoji:"🦭", lat:37.9075, lon:-122.6758, cat:"Wildlife Area", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a9/Bolinas_Lagoon_Marin.jpg/320px-Bolinas_Lagoon_Marin.jpg", fact:"Bolinas Lagoon is one of the most productive <em>harbor seal pupping beaches</em> in Northern California, with over 200 seals hauling out on a sandbar visible from Highway 1. The lagoon sits in a fault-controlled depression formed by the San Andreas Fault, and the water's edge has been slowly creeping inland as the lagoon fills with sediment." },
{ name:"Bolinas — The Town That Removes Its Own Road Signs", county:"Marin", emoji:"🏘", lat:37.9086, lon:-122.6856, cat:"Town", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a9/Bolinas_Lagoon_Marin.jpg/320px-Bolinas_Lagoon_Marin.jpg", fact:"The town of Bolinas has been removing the highway department's road signs pointing to the town for <em>over 50 years</em> in a deliberate effort to discourage tourists — the state replaces the signs, residents steal them again, in an ongoing standoff. The town's 1,600 residents include a higher concentration of poets, artists, and musicians per capita than any other California community." },
{ name:"Tomales Bay", county:"Marin", emoji:"🦪", lat:38.1833, lon:-122.9167, cat:"Bay", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/Tomales_Bay.jpg/320px-Tomales_Bay.jpg", fact:"Tomales Bay occupies a linear valley carved by the <em>San Andreas Fault</em> — the bay's perfectly straight, 15-mile length follows the fault exactly, making it one of the most visible expressions of the fault anywhere on its 800-mile length. The bay's cold, clean water produces some of the finest oysters in the world — Hog Island Oyster Company has farmed here since 1983." },
{ name:"Point Bonita Lighthouse", county:"Marin", emoji:"🔦", lat:37.8161, lon:-122.5289, cat:"Historic Lighthouse", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Point_Bonita_Lighthouse.jpg/320px-Point_Bonita_Lighthouse.jpg", fact:"Point Bonita Lighthouse, first lit in <em>1855</em>, guards one of the most treacherous approaches to a major American port — the narrow, fog-shrouded entrance to San Francisco Bay where currents run at 7 knots. The lighthouse, now accessible only by a 60-foot suspension bridge over a sea-stack, required its own tunnel blasted through solid rock for lighthouse keepers to reach it." },
{ name:"Marin Headlands — GGNRA", county:"Marin", emoji:"🌊", lat:37.8325, lon:-122.5033, cat:"National Recreation Area", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/SF_from_Marin_Headlands_in_January_2013.jpg/320px-SF_from_Marin_Headlands_in_January_2013.jpg", fact:"The Marin Headlands were preserved from development through a <em>congressional bait-and-switch</em> in 1972 — developers had successfully lobbied for a highway through the headlands, and conservationists attached language to the bill that created a national recreation area instead. The headlands' Nike missile batteries from the Cold War are still intact, and one silo is operational for public demonstrations." },
{ name:"Hawk Hill, Marin Headlands", county:"Marin", emoji:"🦅", lat:37.8319, lon:-122.4994, cat:"Wildlife Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2f/Hawk_Hill_Marin_Headlands.jpg/320px-Hawk_Hill_Marin_Headlands.jpg", fact:"Hawk Hill is the <em>best raptor migration observation point</em> on the Pacific Coast — on a good October day, over 2,000 hawks, falcons, and eagles pass directly overhead as they funnel through the narrowest point of the Marin Headlands on their southward migration. The hill's count of over 100,000 raptors observed in a single season is the highest for any site west of the Mississippi." },
{ name:"Kirby Cove", county:"Marin", emoji:"⛺", lat:37.8289, lon:-122.4836, cat:"Beach", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2f/Hawk_Hill_Marin_Headlands.jpg/320px-Hawk_Hill_Marin_Headlands.jpg", fact:"Kirby Cove is a <em>hidden campground</em> directly under the Golden Gate Bridge's north tower, accessible only by a mile-long trail and requiring a reservation made months in advance. The cove's camp sites are so close to the bridge that campers can hear the bridge humming in the wind overhead, and the view of the bridge from the beach at sunset is one of the most dramatic in the Bay Area." },
{ name:"Tennessee Valley Beach", county:"Marin", emoji:"🏖", lat:37.8633, lon:-122.5358, cat:"Beach", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/08/Tennessee_Valley_Beach.jpg/320px-Tennessee_Valley_Beach.jpg", fact:"Tennessee Valley Beach takes its name from the <em>steamship Tennessee</em> that wrecked here in 1853 with 600 passengers aboard — all survived, but the ship's entire cargo of Gold Rush gold was lost. The valley's creek is one of the last undeveloped coastal watersheds in Marin County, and coho salmon still attempt to spawn in its short lower reach." },
{ name:"Muir Beach", county:"Marin", emoji:"🌊", lat:37.8658, lon:-122.5750, cat:"Beach", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/Muir_Beach_CA.jpg/320px-Muir_Beach_CA.jpg", fact:"Muir Beach's lagoon behind the beach is a critical <em>resting and feeding stop</em> for coho salmon returning from the Pacific — the juvenile fish spend months in this lagoon before moving into Redwood Creek for their final journey to spawning grounds. The beach's sheltered position makes it the calmest swimming spot on the Marin coast." },
{ name:"Cascade Canyon Open Space", county:"Marin", emoji:"💧", lat:37.9394, lon:-122.5539, cat:"Open Space", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/Mill_Valley_downtown.jpg/320px-Mill_Valley_downtown.jpg", fact:"Cascade Canyon contains one of the few <em>permanent waterfalls</em> in Marin County, fed by a spring that flows year-round regardless of rainfall. The canyon's redwood grove, though second-growth, is dense enough to support a population of marbled murrelets — seabirds that fly 50 miles inland to nest in old-growth forests, using trees in second-growth groves when old-growth is unavailable." },
{ name:"San Quentin State Prison", county:"Marin", emoji:"🏛", lat:37.9408, lon:-122.4853, cat:"Historic Building", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/San_Quentin_State_Prison.jpg/320px-San_Quentin_State_Prison.jpg", fact:"San Quentin, opened in <em>1852</em>, is the oldest prison in California and has been continuously operated for over 170 years — making it one of the longest-running penitentiaries in American history. The prison's death row has held some of the most notorious criminals in California history, and the current governor has proposed converting the site into a rehabilitation center." },
{ name:"China Camp State Park", county:"Marin", emoji:"🦐", lat:38.0019, lon:-122.4711, cat:"State Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/93/China_Camp_State_Park.jpg/320px-China_Camp_State_Park.jpg", fact:"China Camp was a <em>Chinese immigrant fishing village</em> that thrived from the 1870s to the 1930s, sending dried shrimp by the ton to markets in China and throughout the Pacific. The village's last resident, Frank Quan, lived here alone for decades after everyone else left — continuing to fish from the same piers his grandfather built — and died in 2016 at age 93." },
{ name:"McNears Beach County Park", county:"Marin", emoji:"🏖", lat:37.9894, lon:-122.4703, cat:"County Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/93/China_Camp_State_Park.jpg/320px-China_Camp_State_Park.jpg", fact:"McNears Beach has operated as a public recreation area since <em>1926</em>, when George McNear opened his private quarry beach to the public. The park's heated saltwater pool, filled directly from the bay, is one of the last of its type in the Bay Area — a relic of early 20th-century spa culture that has somehow survived." },
{ name:"San Pedro Mountain Open Space", county:"Marin", emoji:"🌿", lat:37.9919, lon:-122.5400, cat:"Open Space", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/93/China_Camp_State_Park.jpg/320px-China_Camp_State_Park.jpg", fact:"San Pedro Mountain is the <em>highest point in southern Marin County</em> at 1,058 feet, offering views south to the San Francisco skyline and north to Point Reyes. The mountain's chaparral slopes are among the most botanically diverse in Marin County, supporting over 200 plant species in the unique combination of marine fog and summer drought." },
{ name:"Corte Madera Marsh", county:"Marin", emoji:"🦩", lat:37.9258, lon:-122.5325, cat:"Marsh", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Sausalito_waterfront.jpg/320px-Sausalito_waterfront.jpg", fact:"Corte Madera Marsh is one of the <em>most restored tidal marshes</em> in the Bay Area, transformed from former dairy land back to functioning tidal wetland over 30 years of restoration work. The marsh is a critical nursery habitat for Dungeness crab, and researchers tracking crab populations use it as a baseline for measuring the health of the entire bay ecosystem." },
{ name:"Larkspur Ferry Terminal", county:"Marin", emoji:"⛴", lat:37.9456, lon:-122.5089, cat:"Transit", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/46/Tiburon_California.jpg/320px-Tiburon_California.jpg", fact:"The Larkspur Ferry Terminal, opened in <em>1976</em>, connects Marin County to San Francisco by a 30-minute ferry ride that is consistently rated among the most beautiful commutes in the world. The terminal's location adjacent to the former San Quentin Prison industrial zone required massive cleanup of contaminated soils from 19th-century industrial operations." },
{ name:"Baltimore Canyon Open Space", county:"Marin", emoji:"🌲", lat:37.9336, lon:-122.5800, cat:"Open Space", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/Mill_Valley_downtown.jpg/320px-Mill_Valley_downtown.jpg", fact:"Baltimore Canyon's redwood grove includes trees estimated to be <em>over 1,000 years old</em> — among the oldest on the eastern slopes of Mount Tamalpais — that survived because the canyon was too steep and narrow for 19th-century logging equipment to operate efficiently. The canyon's year-round stream creates a microclimate cool enough to support plants normally found much further north." },
{ name:"Mill Valley Historic Downtown", county:"Marin", emoji:"🏘", lat:37.9058, lon:-122.5453, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/Mill_Valley_downtown.jpg/320px-Mill_Valley_downtown.jpg", fact:"Mill Valley earned its name from a sawmill built in <em>1834</em> to cut redwood lumber for the construction of Mission Dolores across the bay. The town's bohemian character dates to the 1890s when artists and writers began building summer cottages in the redwoods, attracted by the new railroad that made the mountain accessible from San Francisco for a weekend escape." },
{ name:"Fairfax — Downtown Historic District", county:"Marin", emoji:"🎸", lat:37.9872, lon:-122.5889, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/Mill_Valley_downtown.jpg/320px-Mill_Valley_downtown.jpg", fact:"Fairfax has been a center of <em>Northern California music and counterculture</em> since the 1960s — the town's small clubs hosted early performances by Jefferson Airplane, the Grateful Dead, and dozens of other Bay Area bands who lived in the surrounding hills. The town's single main street hosts an unusually high concentration of independent bookstores, music venues, and health food restaurants for a town of 7,500 people." },
{ name:"Samuel P. Taylor State Park", county:"Marin", emoji:"🌲", lat:38.0122, lon:-122.7247, cat:"State Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4e/Samuel_P_Taylor_State_Park.jpg/320px-Samuel_P_Taylor_State_Park.jpg", fact:"Samuel P. Taylor State Park contains California's <em>first campground</em>, established by Taylor himself in the 1870s when he opened his paper mill site to San Francisco day-trippers who arrived by train. The Papermill Creek in the park's heart is one of the best coho salmon streams in the Bay Area, and fish can be watched spawning from bridges in December and January." },
{ name:"Nicasio Reservoir", county:"Marin", emoji:"💧", lat:38.0608, lon:-122.6881, cat:"Reservoir", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a9/Bolinas_Lagoon_Marin.jpg/320px-Bolinas_Lagoon_Marin.jpg", fact:"Nicasio Reservoir, completed in <em>1960</em>, flooded the historic valley of Nicasio — home to a dairy community founded by Portuguese Azorean immigrants in the 1850s. The old Nicasio town site, including its adobe church and cemetery, remains partially visible during drought years when water levels drop, emerging from the reservoir like a California Brigadoon." },
{ name:"Lagunitas — Papermill Creek Restoration", county:"Marin", emoji:"🐟", lat:38.0256, lon:-122.7125, cat:"Environmental Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4e/Samuel_P_Taylor_State_Park.jpg/320px-Samuel_P_Taylor_State_Park.jpg", fact:"Papermill Creek in Lagunitas contains the <em>last viable wild coho salmon population</em> in the San Francisco Bay watershed — a strain of fish isolated since the last Ice Age that has developed unique genetic adaptations to the local environment. Extraordinary conservation efforts by local volunteers, including hand-counting every spawning adult each winter, have kept the population from extinction." },
{ name:"Olema Valley", county:"Marin", emoji:"🌾", lat:38.0433, lon:-122.7986, cat:"Valley", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Bear_Valley_Visitor_Center_Point_Reyes.jpg/320px-Bear_Valley_Visitor_Center_Point_Reyes.jpg", fact:"Olema Valley lies directly along the <em>San Andreas Fault</em>, and the valley's unusual linearity — straight as a ruler for miles — is a textbook example of how fault activity shapes landscapes. In 1906, the ground here offset so violently that a cow fell into a crack that opened beneath it, and researchers found the animal buried 8 feet underground in the fault scarp." },
{ name:"Inverness — Historic Village", county:"Marin", emoji:"🏘", lat:38.1000, lon:-122.8600, cat:"Historic Village", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/Tomales_Bay.jpg/320px-Tomales_Bay.jpg", fact:"Inverness was settled by <em>Scottish immigrants</em> who named it for Inverness, Scotland, finding the fog-shrouded hills above Tomales Bay eerily similar to the Scottish Highlands. The village's Scottish character — stone cottages, a Presbyterian church, and a local brewery — has been preserved largely because the surrounding Point Reyes National Seashore prevents suburban development." },
{ name:"Abbotts Lagoon, Point Reyes", county:"Marin", emoji:"🦢", lat:38.1111, lon:-122.9356, cat:"Lagoon", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Bear_Valley_Visitor_Center_Point_Reyes.jpg/320px-Bear_Valley_Visitor_Center_Point_Reyes.jpg", fact:"Abbotts Lagoon is separated from the Pacific Ocean by a narrow dune barrier that is breached by storm waves every few years — allowing salt water to flood the freshwater lagoon in a <em>dramatic ecological reset</em> that resets the plant and animal communities. The lagoon is the best place in the Bay Area to see nesting western snowy plovers." },
{ name:"Drake's Estero, Point Reyes", county:"Marin", emoji:"🦭", lat:38.0786, lon:-122.8958, cat:"Estuary", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Bear_Valley_Visitor_Center_Point_Reyes.jpg/320px-Bear_Valley_Visitor_Center_Point_Reyes.jpg", fact:"Drake's Estero is believed to be the location where <em>Francis Drake careened his ship</em> Golden Hind in 1579 to scrape barnacles during his circumnavigation of the globe — a stay of over a month documented in the ship's log as 'a convenient harbor.' Drake claimed the land for England as 'Nova Albion,' the first European territorial claim in what is now California." },
{ name:"Chimney Rock, Point Reyes", county:"Marin", emoji:"🦭", lat:37.9983, lon:-122.9656, cat:"Natural Landmark", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Bear_Valley_Visitor_Center_Point_Reyes.jpg/320px-Bear_Valley_Visitor_Center_Point_Reyes.jpg", fact:"Chimney Rock at the tip of the Point Reyes headland is where <em>elephant seals began recolonizing</em> California in the 1980s after being hunted to near extinction — starting from zero seals in 1981, the population has grown to over 2,000. The point is also one of the best whale-watching spots on the California coast, with gray whales passing within a few hundred feet of the cliffs during migration." },
{ name:"Bear Valley Visitor Center, Point Reyes", county:"Marin", emoji:"🌿", lat:38.0413, lon:-122.7997, cat:"Visitor Center", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Bear_Valley_Visitor_Center_Point_Reyes.jpg/320px-Bear_Valley_Visitor_Center_Point_Reyes.jpg", fact:"Bear Valley was the <em>last major Coast Miwok village</em> in the Point Reyes area, continuously occupied for over 5,000 years before the Spanish mission system disrupted indigenous society in the early 1800s. The trail from the visitor center to the coast follows the exact path of a Miwok trail documented by the Drake expedition in 1579." },

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════
// SONOMA COUNTY
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════

{ name:"Sonoma Plaza — Bear Flag Republic Site", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🐻", lat:38.2919, lon:-122.4581, cat:"Historic Plaza", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b0/Sonoma_Plaza.jpg/320px-Sonoma_Plaza.jpg", fact:"Sonoma Plaza was the site of the <em>Bear Flag Revolt of 1846</em>, when American settlers captured Mexican General Vallejo and declared the short-lived California Republic — raising a homemade bear flag over the barracks. The republic lasted exactly 25 days before the U.S. Navy arrived and California was absorbed into the United States during the Mexican-American War." },
{ name:"Mission San Francisco Solano de Sonoma", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"⛪", lat:38.2919, lon:-122.4567, cat:"Historic Mission", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2e/Sonoma_Mission.JPG/320px-Sonoma_Mission.JPG", fact:"Mission Solano, founded in <em>1823</em>, was the last and northernmost of California's 21 missions, established just three years before Mexico won independence from Spain. It is also the only mission founded under Mexican rather than Spanish authority — built by a rogue Franciscan priest who acted without authorization from the church hierarchy." },
{ name:"Jack London State Historic Park", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"📚", lat:38.3567, lon:-122.5489, cat:"Historic Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/50/Wolf_House_Jack_London.jpg/320px-Wolf_House_Jack_London.jpg", fact:"Jack London's dream home, the <em>Wolf House</em>, burned to the ground in 1913 just days before he and his wife were to move in — a mysterious fire London suspected was arson. The roofless ruins of the massive stone mansion still stand in the park, while the adjacent 'House of Happy Walls' built by his widow after his death houses a museum of London's life and adventures." },
{ name:"Armstrong Redwoods State Natural Reserve", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🌲", lat:38.5344, lon:-123.0039, cat:"State Reserve", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5e/Armstrong_Redwoods.jpg/320px-Armstrong_Redwoods.jpg", fact:"Armstrong Redwoods protects a grove of ancient coast redwoods that survived 19th-century logging because lumber baron Colonel Armstrong had the foresight to preserve them — creating one of the <em>first private forest preserves</em> in California in the 1870s. The Parson Jones Tree here is 310 feet tall and 1,400 years old — it was a mature tree when the Moors invaded Spain." },
{ name:"Bodega Bay", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🦅", lat:38.3336, lon:-123.0533, cat:"Bay", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/Bodega_Bay_California.jpg/320px-Bodega_Bay_California.jpg", fact:"Bodega Bay was the filming location for Alfred Hitchcock's <em>'The Birds'</em> in 1963, and many of the original buildings used in the film still stand in the town. The bay's exposed position on the open Pacific and its cold, upwelling-fed waters make it one of the most productive fishing grounds on the California coast for Dungeness crab and salmon." },
{ name:"Bodega Head", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🌊", lat:38.3147, lon:-123.0617, cat:"Headland", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/90/Bodega_Head_Sonoma.jpg/320px-Bodega_Head_Sonoma.jpg", fact:"Bodega Head was the proposed site of California's <em>first nuclear power plant</em> in the early 1960s — PG&E had already dug a 70-foot test pit for the reactor when geologists discovered the site sat directly on the San Andreas Fault. The resulting controversy helped establish the antinuclear movement in California and eventually led to the creation of the California Coastal Commission." },
{ name:"Fort Ross State Historic Park", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🏰", lat:38.5133, lon:-123.2428, cat:"Historic Fort", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/56/Fort_Ross_state_historic_park.jpg/320px-Fort_Ross_state_historic_park.jpg", fact:"Fort Ross was a <em>Russian colonial settlement</em> established in 1812 — the southernmost permanent Russian outpost in North America, built to grow food for Russian Alaska and hunt sea otters. The Russians abandoned the fort in 1841 when the sea otter population had been hunted to near-extinction, selling the property to John Sutter, who would later discover gold at his mill in Coloma." },
{ name:"Salt Point State Park", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🦪", lat:38.5697, lon:-123.3283, cat:"State Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2a/Salt_Point_State_Park.jpg/320px-Salt_Point_State_Park.jpg", fact:"Salt Point State Park contains the first <em>underwater park in California</em>, established in 1969 to protect the abalone and other marine life of its rocky reefs from overharvesting. The park's dramatic sandstone formations, honeycombed with tafoni erosion, create an otherworldly landscape along the cliff tops that has been used as a setting in science fiction films." },
{ name:"Gualala Point Regional Park", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🌊", lat:38.7583, lon:-123.5333, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/90/Bodega_Head_Sonoma.jpg/320px-Bodega_Head_Sonoma.jpg", fact:"Gualala takes its name from the Coast Miwok word meaning <em>'water coming down place'</em>, referring to the Gualala River that meets the Pacific here. The river mouth's lagoon, cut off from the ocean by a sandbar each summer, is a critical habitat for steelhead trout that wait in the lagoon for winter rains to open the bar before making their spawning run." },
{ name:"Petaluma Adobe State Historic Park", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🏚", lat:38.2539, lon:-122.6086, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/38/Petaluma_Adobe.jpg/320px-Petaluma_Adobe.jpg", fact:"General Mariano Vallejo's Petaluma Adobe, built in <em>1836</em>, was the largest private adobe structure in California and the headquarters of a rancho that ran 10,000 cattle and 10,000 sheep across 66,000 acres — the largest private ranch in California history. The two-story adobe with its surrounding workshops was essentially a self-contained town, employing over 2,000 Miwok and Pomo workers." },
{ name:"Petaluma Historic Downtown", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🏘", lat:38.2324, lon:-122.6367, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e5/Petaluma_downtown.jpg/320px-Petaluma_downtown.jpg", fact:"Petaluma was the <em>egg capital of the world</em> from the 1880s to the 1960s, producing over 600 million eggs per year at its peak and earning the title 'World's Egg Basket.' The town's Victorian commercial district along the river is one of the most intact 19th-century Main Streets in California — its cast-iron facades have been used as film sets for dozens of period movies." },
{ name:"Petaluma River Historic District", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🌊", lat:38.2325, lon:-122.6392, cat:"Historic Waterfront", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e5/Petaluma_downtown.jpg/320px-Petaluma_downtown.jpg", fact:"The Petaluma River, navigable for 14 miles inland, made the city one of the most important <em>agricultural shipping ports</em> in Northern California from the 1850s through the railroad era. The river's reversing tidal current — it flows upstream twice a day — was used by farmers to float barges of butter, eggs, and poultry to San Francisco without any power." },
{ name:"Sonoma Valley — Wine Country", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🍷", lat:38.2919, lon:-122.4581, cat:"Wine Region", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/19/Sonoma_Valley_vineyards.jpg/320px-Sonoma_Valley_vineyards.jpg", fact:"Sonoma Valley was California's <em>first commercial wine region</em> — Count Agoston Haraszthy planted the first large-scale European varietal vineyard at Buena Vista in 1857, importing 100,000 cuttings from 300 European varieties. The valley's diverse geology — volcanic, alluvial, and marine sedimentary soils — produces wine grapes of extraordinary variety within a small geographic area." },
{ name:"Buena Vista Winery, Sonoma", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🍇", lat:38.2986, lon:-122.4436, cat:"Historic Winery", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/Buena_Vista_Winery.jpg/320px-Buena_Vista_Winery.jpg", fact:"Buena Vista, founded in <em>1857</em>, is the oldest continuously operating winery in California — its limestone caves, hand-dug by Chinese laborers, are still used for barrel aging. Count Haraszthy, who founded the winery, disappeared in 1869 on a business trip to Nicaragua and was never found — his family believed he was eaten by alligators." },
{ name:"Healdsburg Plaza", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🌳", lat:38.6110, lon:-122.8697, cat:"Historic Plaza", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/Healdsburg_Plaza.jpg/320px-Healdsburg_Plaza.jpg", fact:"Healdsburg's central plaza, surrounded by tasting rooms and restaurants, was laid out in <em>1857</em> on land donated by Harmon Heald, who platted the town as a real estate speculation. The town has transformed from a hop-growing agricultural center to one of the most visited wine destinations in California — Michelin-starred restaurants now occupy buildings that were once feed stores." },
{ name:"Russian River Valley", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🍷", lat:38.5000, lon:-122.9000, cat:"Wine Region", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/Russian_River_Valley_vineyards.jpg/320px-Russian_River_Valley_vineyards.jpg", fact:"The Russian River Valley's unique climate, where <em>morning fog burns off by noon</em> then returns each evening, creates a natural refrigeration system that preserves acidity in Chardonnay and Pinot Noir grapes — varieties that fail in warmer climates. The valley was named for the Russian colonists from Fort Ross who used the river as a supply route in the early 1800s." },
{ name:"Guerneville — Riverfront Historic District", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🌲", lat:38.5022, lon:-122.9989, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/Russian_River_Valley_vineyards.jpg/320px-Russian_River_Valley_vineyards.jpg", fact:"Guerneville was the center of the Sonoma County <em>redwood lumber industry</em> in the 1870s-1890s, when it was known as 'Stumptown' for the massive clear-cut stumps surrounding the town. After logging moved north, the town reinvented itself as a summer resort for San Francisco vacationers and later became a center of LGBT culture in the 1970s." },
{ name:"Monte Rio — Rio Nido Historic Summer Cabins", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🏕", lat:38.4656, lon:-123.0050, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/Russian_River_Valley_vineyards.jpg/320px-Russian_River_Valley_vineyards.jpg", fact:"The Russian River resort communities were built in the <em>1910s-1920s</em> as summer retreats for San Francisco working-class families who could afford a train ticket but not a hotel — the 'Poor Man's Riviera.' Hundreds of simple wooden cabins, some little changed in a century, cluster under the redwoods in a landscape of shaded swimming holes and old dancehalls." },
{ name:"Bohemian Grove", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🌲", lat:38.4706, lon:-123.0175, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/Russian_River_Valley_vineyards.jpg/320px-Russian_River_Valley_vineyards.jpg", fact:"Bohemian Grove is a 2,700-acre private redwood retreat where the <em>Bohemian Club of San Francisco</em> has held its annual midsummer encampment since 1878, hosting every Republican president since Herbert Hoover. The grove's secretive 'Cremation of Care' ceremony, a theatrical ritual burning of an effigy, has fueled decades of conspiracy theories about what actually happens inside." },
{ name:"Occidental — Historic Logging Town", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🌲", lat:38.4058, lon:-122.9536, cat:"Historic Town", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/Annadel_State_Park.jpg/320px-Annadel_State_Park.jpg", fact:"Occidental sits in a valley that was completely <em>clear-cut of old-growth redwood</em> between 1876 and 1890, supplying lumber for the rebuilding of San Francisco after a series of fires. The current forest, now over 130 years old, has grown back so completely that the town appears to sit in a primeval forest — the scale of the original destruction is almost unimaginable today." },
{ name:"Duncans Mills Historic Town", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🏘", lat:38.4581, lon:-123.0489, cat:"Historic Town", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/Russian_River_Valley_vineyards.jpg/320px-Russian_River_Valley_vineyards.jpg", fact:"Duncans Mills was the highest point navigable by steamboat on the Russian River, making it the <em>transfer point</em> between river and overland transportation during the logging era. The town's original 1870s buildings — a general store, hotel, and church — still stand along the river, preserved because the area's isolation prevented redevelopment." },
{ name:"Jenner — Russian River Mouth", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🦭", lat:38.4528, lon:-123.1139, cat:"Natural Feature", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/90/Bodega_Head_Sonoma.jpg/320px-Bodega_Head_Sonoma.jpg", fact:"The Russian River's mouth at Jenner supports one of the <em>largest harbor seal pupping colonies</em> in the Bay Area — over 300 mothers and pups use the river mouth sandbars each spring. The river mouth is closed by a sandbar for most of the year, opening explosively when winter rains raise the river high enough to break through the barrier in a dramatic rush of water." },
{ name:"Sonoma Coast State Park", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🌊", lat:38.5333, lon:-123.2000, cat:"State Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/90/Bodega_Head_Sonoma.jpg/320px-Bodega_Head_Sonoma.jpg", fact:"Sonoma Coast's <em>'Pocket beaches'</em> between dramatic sea stacks are among the most photographed coastline in California, but their deceptive beauty hides some of the most dangerous surf conditions on the West Coast — sneaker waves and powerful backwash have killed hundreds of visitors over the decades. The coast's rocks are among the most geologically diverse on the Pacific Coast." },
{ name:"Sea Ranch — Historic Architecture Community", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🏠", lat:38.7047, lon:-123.4736, cat:"Historic Architecture", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/90/Bodega_Head_Sonoma.jpg/320px-Bodega_Head_Sonoma.jpg", fact:"The Sea Ranch, developed in the 1960s by landscape architect Lawrence Halprin, established principles of <em>architecture in harmony with landscape</em> that influenced residential design worldwide. The community's design rules — no fences, weathered wood exteriors, buildings that follow terrain contours — sparked a legal battle that established public access to California's coast and led directly to the creation of the Coastal Commission." },
{ name:"Cazadero — Stillwater Cove", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🌲", lat:38.5117, lon:-123.1467, cat:"Natural Area", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2a/Salt_Point_State_Park.jpg/320px-Salt_Point_State_Park.jpg", fact:"Stillwater Cove's protected waters were used by Russian colonists from Fort Ross as a <em>small boat harbor</em> in the early 1800s, sheltered from Pacific swells by a natural rock breakwater. The cove's underwater kelp forest is among the most intact on the Sonoma coast, supporting populations of rockfish and lingcod that have rebounded since the area became a reserve." },
{ name:"Cloverdale Historic Downtown", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🍊", lat:38.8025, lon:-123.0186, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/Healdsburg_Plaza.jpg/320px-Healdsburg_Plaza.jpg", fact:"Cloverdale was the <em>northernmost stop on the Northwestern Pacific Railroad</em>, making it the gateway to the Mendocino and Humboldt lumber country — a rough railroad town that served loggers and ranchers heading north. The town's citrus orchards, planted in the 1880s, still produce oranges and lemons in the warm valley microclimate that is the northern limit for commercial citrus in California." },
{ name:"Geysers Geothermal Area", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"♨️", lat:38.7833, lon:-122.7333, cat:"Geothermal", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/56/Sugarloaf_Ridge_State_Park.jpg/320px-Sugarloaf_Ridge_State_Park.jpg", fact:"The Geysers is the <em>largest geothermal power complex in the world</em>, generating enough electricity to power San Francisco from naturally occurring steam vented from magma chambers miles underground. The area has been known since the 1800s when tourists came by stagecoach to see the fumaroles — the local Pomo people considered the steam vents sacred and used them for healing ceremonies." },
{ name:"Lake Sonoma Recreation Area", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"💧", lat:38.7117, lon:-123.0283, cat:"Recreation Area", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/56/Sugarloaf_Ridge_State_Park.jpg/320px-Sugarloaf_Ridge_State_Park.jpg", fact:"Lake Sonoma, created by Warm Springs Dam in <em>1983</em>, was the last federal water project built in California before environmental opposition made new dam construction effectively impossible. The reservoir flooded a valley of ranches and orchards — one ranch family held out for 40 years in legal battles before finally accepting compensation when the water rose around their property." },
{ name:"Dry Creek Valley Wine Country", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🍇", lat:38.6500, lon:-122.9500, cat:"Wine Region", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/Paso_Robles_wine_country.jpg/320px-Paso_Robles_wine_country.jpg", fact:"Dry Creek Valley's bench lands of well-drained alluvial soil, surrounded by hills that block coastal fog, create conditions <em>nearly identical to the Bordeaux wine region</em> in France — a resemblance that allowed the valley to establish Zinfandel and Cabernet Sauvignon as its signature varieties. The valley's family-owned wineries, many established by Italian immigrant families in the 1880s, have resisted corporate buyouts more successfully than any other Sonoma wine region." },
{ name:"Alexander Valley Wine Country", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🍷", lat:38.7500, lon:-122.9000, cat:"Wine Region", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/19/Sonoma_Valley_vineyards.jpg/320px-Sonoma_Valley_vineyards.jpg", fact:"Alexander Valley's long, warm growing season produces the <em>richest and most powerful Cabernet Sauvignons</em> in Sonoma County — wines that compete directly with Napa Valley's most prestigious bottles at a fraction of the price. The valley was settled by Cyrus Alexander in 1840, who received a land grant from General Vallejo in exchange for managing the general's rancho in the north." },
{ name:"Rohnert Park — Cotati Historic Railroad Depot", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🚂", lat:38.3394, lon:-122.7103, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e5/Petaluma_downtown.jpg/320px-Petaluma_downtown.jpg", fact:"The Cotati depot was a stop on the <em>Northwestern Pacific Railroad</em> that once connected San Francisco to Eureka — a 286-mile journey that took 12 hours through some of the most dramatic scenery in California. The railroad, killed by automobile competition in the 1930s and 1940s, is now being revived as a commuter rail line." },
{ name:"Santa Rosa — Railroad Square Historic District", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🏘", lat:38.4393, lon:-122.7269, cat:"Historic District", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/13/Charles_M_Schulz_Museum.jpg/320px-Charles_M_Schulz_Museum.jpg", fact:"Railroad Square was rebuilt after the <em>1906 earthquake</em> leveled most of downtown Santa Rosa — the city suffered worse damage proportionally than San Francisco, but received far less attention and aid. The square's stone and brick buildings, constructed from local quarried stone after 1906, form one of the most complete early 20th-century commercial districts in Northern California." },
{ name:"Charles M. Schulz Museum, Santa Rosa", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🐕", lat:38.4381, lon:-122.7175, cat:"Museum", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/13/Charles_M_Schulz_Museum.jpg/320px-Charles_M_Schulz_Museum.jpg", fact:"Charles Schulz, creator of Peanuts, lived in Santa Rosa for the last <em>30 years of his life</em> and drew every single one of his 17,897 Peanuts strips in his studio here — working until two months before his death in 2000. The museum's highlight is a recreation of his actual studio, preserved exactly as he left it." },
{ name:"Luther Burbank Home and Gardens, Santa Rosa", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🌹", lat:38.4408, lon:-122.7142, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4d/Luther_Burbank_Home_Santa_Rosa.jpg/320px-Luther_Burbank_Home_Santa_Rosa.jpg", fact:"Luther Burbank developed over <em>800 new plant varieties</em> in his Santa Rosa gardens — including the Shasta daisy, the Freestone peach, the Santa Rosa plum, and the Russet Burbank potato used in McDonald's French fries. Burbank's experimental methods, crossing thousands of plants over decades, anticipated modern agricultural genetics by 50 years." },
{ name:"Sonoma County Museum, Santa Rosa", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🏛", lat:38.4383, lon:-122.7139, cat:"Museum", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/13/Charles_M_Schulz_Museum.jpg/320px-Charles_M_Schulz_Museum.jpg", fact:"The Sonoma County Museum occupies the <em>original 1910 Federal Building</em>, a Beaux-Arts post office and courthouse that survived the 2017 Tubbs Fire that destroyed thousands of homes around it. The building's thick stone walls and copper roof protected it from embers that consumed the surrounding neighborhood." },
{ name:"Annadel State Park", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🌿", lat:38.4500, lon:-122.6400, cat:"State Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/Annadel_State_Park.jpg/320px-Annadel_State_Park.jpg", fact:"Annadel State Park's cobblestone quarries, worked from the <em>1870s to 1950s</em>, paved the streets of San Francisco — the distinctive round stones underfoot in many historic SF neighborhoods came from this exact hillside. The quarry pits have since filled with water and now serve as swimming holes for the park's summer visitors." },
{ name:"Sugarloaf Ridge State Park", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"⭐", lat:38.4333, lon:-122.5167, cat:"State Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/56/Sugarloaf_Ridge_State_Park.jpg/320px-Sugarloaf_Ridge_State_Park.jpg", fact:"Sugarloaf Ridge's astronomy program operates one of the best <em>public observatories</em> in Northern California — the Sonoma Valley Observatory, with a 40-inch telescope, on weekends when skies are clear. The park's ridgeline sits above the marine layer that obscures coastal skies, making it one of the darkest accessible sites in the Bay Area." },
{ name:"Hood Mountain Regional Park", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🏔", lat:38.4667, lon:-122.5333, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/56/Sugarloaf_Ridge_State_Park.jpg/320px-Sugarloaf_Ridge_State_Park.jpg", fact:"Hood Mountain's 2,730-foot summit offers the <em>highest publicly accessible viewpoint</em> in Sonoma County, with views stretching from the Pacific coast to the Sacramento Valley on clear days. The mountain's upper slopes were severely burned in the 2017 Nuns Fire, and the recovery of native chaparral species has been closely watched by botanists studying post-fire plant succession." },
{ name:"Crane Creek Regional Park", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🦅", lat:38.3978, lon:-122.6011, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/Annadel_State_Park.jpg/320px-Annadel_State_Park.jpg", fact:"Crane Creek's grassland ridges are one of the best places in Sonoma County to observe <em>white-tailed kites</em> — a hawk-like raptor that hovers in place while hunting mice — along with golden eagles and prairie falcons. The park's 128 acres are managed with cattle grazing to maintain the short-grass habitat that these open-country raptors require." },
{ name:"Helen Putnam Regional Park, Petaluma", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🌾", lat:38.2036, lon:-122.6708, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e5/Petaluma_downtown.jpg/320px-Petaluma_downtown.jpg", fact:"Helen Putnam Park's rolling hills were a <em>dairy farm</em> operated by the Putnam family for three generations before being donated to the county in 1975. The park's unobstructed grassland ridges offer views of both the San Pablo Bay and the Petaluma Gap — the wind channel through the Coast Ranges that is one of the windiest spots in the Bay Area." },
{ name:"Tolay Lake Regional Park", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"💧", lat:38.2589, lon:-122.5764, cat:"Regional Park", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/19/Sonoma_Valley_vineyards.jpg/320px-Sonoma_Valley_vineyards.jpg", fact:"Tolay Lake was a sacred site for the <em>Coast Miwok and Southern Pomo peoples</em> for thousands of years — a seasonal lake that attracted vast concentrations of waterfowl and provided an important gathering place for trade and ceremony. The lake dried up when the surrounding ranches drained it for agriculture in the 1880s; restoration work is slowly returning seasonal water to the ancient lake bed." },
{ name:"Sonoma Raceway", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🏎", lat:38.1611, lon:-122.4547, cat:"Raceway", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/60/Sonoma_Raceway.jpg/320px-Sonoma_Raceway.jpg", fact:"Sonoma Raceway's road course winds through <em>12 turns over 2.52 miles</em> on a hillside above the Sonoma Valley, creating one of the most challenging and scenic racing venues in North America. The track was built in 1968 on land that is simultaneously a working vineyard — grapevines grow right up to the track barriers, and wine is made from the grapes harvested during racing season." },
{ name:"General Vallejo's Lachryma Montis, Sonoma", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🏠", lat:38.2972, lon:-122.4650, cat:"Historic Site", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a1/Lachryma_Montis_Sonoma.jpg/320px-Lachryma_Montis_Sonoma.jpg", fact:"General Mariano Vallejo, the most powerful man in Mexican California, built his New England-style Victorian home in Sonoma in <em>1852</em> — a deliberate statement about his embrace of American culture after California statehood. Vallejo named the estate 'Lachryma Montis' (Tears of the Mountain) for a natural spring on the property that he piped into his home for running water — the first private house in California to have indoor plumbing." },
{ name:"Sonoma Barracks State Historic Park", county:"Sonoma", emoji:"🏛", lat:38.2919, lon:-122.4572, cat:"Historic Military", photo:"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Sonoma_Barracks.jpg/320px-Sonoma_Barracks.jpg", fact:"The Sonoma Barracks, built by General Vallejo in <em>1836-1840</em>, were the northernmost military outpost of Mexico in California and housed the soldiers responsible for controlling the territory north of San Francisco Bay. It was from this barracks that American settlers took Vallejo prisoner in 1846, beginning the Bear Flag Revolt that eventually led to California statehood." },

];
